const a = [
  {"id":391,"text":"Which nucleus of the hypothalamus is involved in the regulation of thirst and hunger?","explanation":"The **lateral nucleus** of the hypothalamus is involved in the regulation of both thirst and hunger.\r\n\r\n1. **Thirst Regulation:** The lateral hypothalamic area contains neurons that are responsible for triggering thirst sensations. When the body's water levels are low or when there is an increase in the concentration of solutes in the blood, these neurons are activated, leading to the sensation of thirst. Thirst is an essential mechanism that helps maintain proper water balance in the body.\r\n\r\n2. **Hunger Regulation:** The lateral hypothalamic area also plays a significant role in the regulation of hunger. Neurons in this region are involved in stimulating appetite and food intake. When these neurons are activated, it leads to feelings of hunger and an increased desire to eat.","reference":"Snell RS. Clinical Neuroanatomy. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer Health/Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2010: 390.","responses":[{"text":"Paraventricular nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventromedial nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Supraoptic nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suprachiasmatic nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral nucleus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":2856,"text":"Which artery supplies the infundibulum?","explanation":"The **superior hypophyseal artery** supplies the infundibulum of the pituitary gland. The pituitary gland, also known as the hypophysis, is a small endocrine gland located at the base of the brain in a bony cavity called the sella turcica.\r\n\r\nThe superior hypophyseal artery is a branch of the **internal carotid artery** and is responsible for supplying blood to the upper part of the pituitary gland, which includes the infundibulum and the neural stalk that connects the hypothalamus to the pituitary gland. The infundibulum is a funnel-shaped structure that extends from the hypothalamus to the posterior lobe of the pituitary gland (neurohypophysis).","reference":"Superior hypophysial artery - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 17, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/neuroscience/superior-hypophysial-artery","responses":[{"text":"Basilar artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal carotid artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"External carotid artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior hypophyseal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior hypophyseal artery","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":2884,"text":"Which of the following is decreased by somatostatin?","explanation":"**Somatostatin**, also known as growth hormone-inhibiting hormone (GHIH), is a peptide hormone produced by the delta cells of the pancreas and certain other tissues in the body. It exerts inhibitory effects on various physiological processes, including the regulation of hormone secretion.\r\n\r\nOne of the main actions of somatostatin is the inhibition of the secretion of both **insulin** and **glucagon**. Insulin is a hormone produced by beta cells in the pancreas and is responsible for lowering blood glucose levels by promoting the uptake and utilization of glucose by cells. Glucagon, on the other hand, is produced by alpha cells in the pancreas and increases blood glucose levels by promoting the breakdown of glycogen into glucose and stimulating gluconeogenesis.\r\n\r\nBy inhibiting the secretion of both insulin and glucagon, somatostatin helps maintain stable blood glucose levels and prevents wide fluctuations in glucose concentration.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 983.","responses":[{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cortisol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Both insulin and glucagon","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucagon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aldosterone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2912,"text":"Which of the following is an accurate and simple parameter, requiring no calculation, to assess central obesity?","explanation":"**Waist circumference** is an accurate and simple parameter that requires no calculation to assess central obesity. Central obesity refers to the excessive accumulation of fat in the abdominal area and is associated with an increased risk of various health conditions, including type 2 diabetes, cardiovascular diseases, and metabolic syndrome.\r\n\r\nTo measure waist circumference, a flexible measuring tape is placed around the waist, just above the hip bones. The measurement is taken at the end of normal expiration, with the tape snug but not compressing the skin.\r\n\r\nCentral obesity, as indicated by an elevated waist circumference, is an essential component of metabolic syndrome, which includes a cluster of risk factors for cardiovascular diseases and type 2 diabetes. It is a simple and valuable screening tool for identifying individuals at higher risk of obesity-related health issues.","reference":"(1) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 700, 744.\r\n\r\n(2) Schunkert H, Markus MRP, Stritzke J, Preedy VR. Waist circumference and cardiovascular risk. Handbook of Anthropometry: Physical Measures of Human Form in Health and Disease. Published 2012. Accessed June 20, 2022. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4419-1788-1_131","responses":[{"text":"Waist circumference","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Weight measurement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood cholesterol levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Body mass index","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Weight-to-height ratio","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2920,"text":"Which of the following is not observed in the inferior part of the hypothalamus when it is viewed from below?","explanation":"When viewed from below, the **tegmentum** is not observed in the inferior part of the hypothalamus. The tegmentum is a portion of the midbrain, specifically the ventral part, and it is located superior to the inferior part of the hypothalamus.\r\n\r\nThe other structures mentioned are observed in the inferior part of the hypothalamus when viewed from below:\r\n\r\n1. **Mammillary bodies:** These are two small, rounded structures located posterior to the hypothalamus and are involved in memory and olfactory processing.\r\n\r\n2. **Optic chiasma:** The optic chiasma is a crucial junction where the optic nerves (CN II) partially cross, just below the hypothalamus, allowing information from the left visual field to be transmitted to the right hemisphere of the brain and vice versa.\r\n\r\n3. **Infundibulum:** This is a stalk-like structure that connects the hypothalamus to the pituitary gland (hypophysis).\r\n\r\n4. **Tuber cinereum:** This is a rounded eminence in the inferior hypothalamus, situated between the mammillary bodies and the infundibulum.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Endocrinology module, Subject: Anatomy, Topic: Gross structure of the Hypothalamus, Sub-topic: Boundaries of Hypothalamus.","responses":[{"text":"Mammillary bodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infundibulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuber cinereum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tegmentum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Optic chiasma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2962,"text":"If the growth hormone level in the blood is increased due to a tumor of the pituitary gland, then which cells of the pituitary gland are most likely affected by the tumor?","explanation":"If the growth hormone (GH) level in the blood is increased due to a tumor of the pituitary gland, the cells most likely affected by the tumor are **somatotropes**. Somatotropes are the specialized cells in the anterior pituitary gland responsible for producing and secreting growth hormone (GH or somatotropin).\r\n\r\nA tumor of the pituitary gland, specifically an adenoma, can cause excess production of GH, leading to a condition known as **acromegaly** in adults or **gigantism** in children and adolescents. Acromegaly is characterized by the enlargement of bones and tissues, particularly in the hands, feet, face, and internal organs, due to the overproduction of GH.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 930.","responses":[{"text":"Somatotropes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyrotropes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lactotropes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gonadotropes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corticotropes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2996,"text":"Steroid hormones bind to which of the following structures?","explanation":"Steroid hormones bind to **hormone response elements (HREs)** in DNA. Steroid hormones, such as cortisol, aldosterone, and sex hormones (estrogen, progesterone, and testosterone), are lipid-soluble molecules that can easily cross cell membranes. Once inside the target cell, they bind to specific receptors, known as **steroid hormone receptors**, located in the cytoplasm or nucleus.\r\n\r\nThe hormone-receptor complex then translocates to the nucleus and binds to specific DNA sequences called hormone response elements (HREs) within the promoter regions of target genes. This binding initiates a series of events that lead to changes in gene transcription and, ultimately, protein synthesis. The newly synthesized proteins mediate the biological effects of the steroid hormones.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 923.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"G-protein coupled receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hormone response element in DNA","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Second messengers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enzyme linked receptors","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3018,"text":"What is the simplest parameter to define obesity in metabolic syndrome?","explanation":"In the context of metabolic syndrome, **waist circumference** is the simplest parameter used to define obesity. Metabolic syndrome is a cluster of risk factors that increase the risk of cardiovascular diseases and diabetes. Central obesity, which refers to excess fat accumulation around the waist, is a key component of metabolic syndrome.\r\n\r\nWaist circumference is a practical and non-invasive measurement that reflects the amount of visceral fat, which is the fat surrounding the abdominal organs. It is considered an indicator of abdominal obesity and an important predictor of metabolic abnormalities.\r\n\r\nThe cutoff values for defining central obesity vary based on population and ethnicity, but generally, a waist circumference above a certain threshold is indicative of central obesity. For example, in adults, a waist circumference greater than 40 inches (102 cm) in men and greater than 35 inches (88 cm) in women is often used to define central obesity in the context of metabolic syndrome.","reference":"(1) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 700, 744. (2) Schunkert H, Markus MRP, Stritzke J, Preedy VR. Waist circumference and cardiovascular risk. Handbook of Anthropometry: Physical Measures of Human Form in Health and Disease. Published 2012. Accessed June 20, 2022. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4419-1788-1_13","responses":[{"text":"Body weight","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Body mass index","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Measurement of visceral fat by MRI scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Waist circumference","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Waist hip ratio","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3040,"text":"Which of the following is the effect of propylthiouracil on thyroid hormone?","explanation":"Propylthiouracil (PTU) is an antithyroid drug used in the treatment of hyperthyroidism. Its primary mechanism of action involves inhibition of thyroid hormone synthesis.\r\n\r\nSpecifically, PTU exerts its effect on the thyroid gland by inhibiting two key steps in thyroid hormone synthesis:\r\n\r\n1. **Inhibition of oxidation of iodide:** The thyroid gland actively takes up iodide from the bloodstream using the sodium-iodide symporter (NIS) on the apical membrane of thyrocytes. PTU inhibits the enzyme thyroid peroxidase (TPO), which is responsible for the oxidation of iodide to iodine within the thyroid follicular cells. This inhibits the formation of iodine radicals necessary for the synthesis of thyroid hormones.\r\n\r\n2. **Inhibition of coupling of iodine:** After iodine is oxidized, it is attached to tyrosine residues on thyroglobulin, a protein within the colloid of thyroid follicles. PTU further inhibits the enzyme TPO from catalyzing the coupling of iodine residues on thyroglobulin, preventing the formation of T3 and T4 (triiodothyronine and thyroxine).","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 308.","responses":[{"text":"Inhibit T3 release from thyroglobulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyper activates Na-I symporter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits oxidation of iodide and coupling of iodine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inactivates thyroglobulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertrophy of thyroid follicles","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3049,"text":"Regarding the development of pituitary gland, which of the following is true?","explanation":"The pituitary gland, also known as the hypophysis, is a crucial endocrine gland responsible for producing and secreting various hormones that regulate numerous physiological processes in the body. Its development involves the formation of distinct parts derived from different embryonic tissues.\r\n\r\n1. **Hypophyseal Diverticulum:** The pituitary gland develops from a depression of the oral ectoderm known as the hypophyseal diverticulum or Rathke's pouch. During the 3rd week of gestation, this pouch forms as an upward projection from the roof of the stomodeum (primitive mouth cavity).\r\n\r\n2. **Ectodermal Origin:** The hypophyseal diverticulum is purely ectodermal in origin. It is not derived from mesoderm or endoderm. As the embryo continues to develop, the Rathke's pouch undergoes complex processes of invagination, proliferation, and differentiation to give rise to the adenohypophysis (anterior pituitary).\r\n\r\n3. **Pars Nervosa:** The pars nervosa, also known as the neurohypophysis (posterior pituitary), develops from neuroectodermal tissue in the diencephalon known as the infundibulum. Nerve fibers from the hypothalamus grow downward along the infundibulum to establish connections with the pars nervosa.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia M. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 9th ed. Elsevier; 2011: 409.","responses":[{"text":"The entire gland develops from Rathke's pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The hypophyseal diverticulum loses its connection from the stomodeum by twelfth week","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is purely ectodermal in origin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypophyseal diverticulum arises from the floor of stomodeum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars nervosa develops from Rathke's pouch","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3103,"text":"A 35-year-old female went to see her doctor because she had been feeling hot lately and was sweating at night. Her T3 and T4 levels were found to be high, whereas her TSH level was low. What is the most likely diagnosis made by the doctor?","explanation":"The clinical scenario described in the case is characteristic of **primary hyperthyroidism**, also known as **thyrotoxicosis**. In this condition, the thyroid gland itself is overproducing thyroid hormones (T3 and T4), leading to an increased concentration of these hormones in the bloodstream. The key laboratory findings in primary hyperthyroidism are high levels of T3 and T4 and low levels of thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH).\r\n\r\n**Possible Causes of Primary Hyperthyroidism:**\r\n- **Graves' Disease:** An autoimmune disorder where autoantibodies stimulate the thyroid gland to produce excessive hormones.\r\n- **Toxic Multinodular Goiter:** The presence of multiple nodules in the thyroid gland, some of which are autonomously producing hormones.\r\n- **Toxic Adenoma:** A single thyroid nodule that autonomously produces excessive hormones.\r\n\r\n**Differential Diagnosis:**\r\n- **Pituitary Adenoma:** A tumor of the pituitary gland that could lead to increased TSH secretion, causing secondary hyperthyroidism.\r\n- **Secondary Hyperthyroidism:** Excessive TSH secretion from the pituitary gland, leading to increased thyroid hormone production.\r\n- **Hypothyroidism:** Low T3 and T4 levels and elevated TSH levels are characteristic of this condition.\r\n- **Myxedema:** A severe form of hypothyroidism, not applicable in this case.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 346.","responses":[{"text":"Primary hyperthyroidism","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothyroidism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myxedema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pituitary adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary hyperthyroidism","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3104,"text":"Which of the following cells produce calcitonin?","explanation":"**Calcitonin** is a hormone that plays a crucial role in calcium homeostasis. It is produced and secreted by the **parafollicular cells**, also known as **C-cells**, which are specialized cells located within the thyroid gland.\r\n\r\nThe thyroid gland is primarily composed of thyroid follicles, which are spherical structures containing colloid. The thyroid follicular cells within these follicles produce and secrete the thyroid hormones, namely **thyroxine (T4)** and **triiodothyronine (T3)**.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, the parafollicular cells are located between the thyroid follicles. These cells are responsible for synthesizing and releasing calcitonin in response to high blood calcium levels. Calcitonin acts to lower blood calcium levels by inhibiting bone resorption and enhancing calcium excretion by the kidneys.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1002.","responses":[{"text":"Chief cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parafollicular cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Islets of Langerhans","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chromaffin cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid follicular cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3123,"text":"The inferior parathyroid glands develop from which of the following?","explanation":"The parathyroid glands, which are responsible for regulating calcium levels in the body, develop from the pharyngeal pouches during embryonic development. The superior parathyroid glands arise from the **fourth pharyngeal pouch**, while the **inferior parathyroid glands** develop from the **dorsal wing of the third pharyngeal pouch**.\r\n\r\n**Embryonic Development of Parathyroid Glands:**\r\n1. Superior Parathyroid Glands: Develop from the **fourth pharyngeal pouch**, which also gives rise to the ultimobranchial body, the precursor of the parafollicular (C) cells of the thyroid gland.\r\n2. Inferior Parathyroid Glands: Arise from the **dorsal wing of the third pharyngeal pouch**, along with the thymus, which develops from the ventral wing of the same pouch.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 163.","responses":[{"text":"Dorsal 2nd pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsal 3rd pharyngeal pouch","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsal 4th pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral 4th pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral 3rd pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3191,"text":"Adrenergic receptors are present in all of the following except:","explanation":"Adrenergic receptors are a type of G-protein-coupled receptors that bind to catecholamines, such as adrenaline (epinephrine) and noradrenaline (norepinephrine). These receptors are classified into two main subtypes: alpha-adrenergic receptors and beta-adrenergic receptors.\r\n\r\n- **Heart:** Adrenergic receptors are present in the heart, and their stimulation leads to an increase in heart rate and force of contraction. Beta-1 adrenergic receptors are predominant in cardiac tissue.\r\n\r\n- **Skeletal Muscle:** Adrenergic receptors are present in skeletal muscle, and their activation causes vasodilation, leading to increased blood flow and oxygen delivery during physical activity. Beta-2 adrenergic receptors are found in skeletal muscle.\r\n\r\n- **Viscera and Intestines:** Adrenergic receptors are present in various visceral organs and intestines, where their activation can lead to smooth muscle contraction or relaxation, depending on the receptor subtype.\r\n\r\n- **Bone:** Unlike the other mentioned tissues, bone tissue does not possess adrenergic receptors. Adrenergic receptors are not involved in the regulation of bone function.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 767.","responses":[{"text":"Bone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Heart","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestines","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skeletal muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Viscera","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3286,"text":"Diabetes insipidus is caused by deficiency of which hormone?","explanation":"Diabetes insipidus (DI) is a disorder characterized by excessive thirst and the production of large volumes of dilute urine. It is caused by the deficiency or inadequate action of **antidiuretic hormone (ADH)**, also known as vasopressin. ADH is produced by the hypothalamus and released by the posterior pituitary gland in response to low blood volume or increased plasma osmolality.\r\n\r\nThe primary function of ADH is to regulate water balance by increasing water reabsorption in the kidney's collecting ducts, leading to the concentration of urine and the preservation of body water. In diabetes insipidus, the lack of ADH leads to the failure of the kidneys to reabsorb water properly, resulting in the excretion of large volumes of dilute urine and causing dehydration and excessive thirst.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 938-939.","responses":[{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aldosterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ADH","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Angiotensin II","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"FSH","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3303,"text":"The pancreatic tail is present anterior to which structure?","explanation":"The **pancreas** is a glandular organ that plays a crucial role in digestion and glucose regulation. It is located in the upper abdomen, posterior to the stomach and adjacent to several other structures.\r\n\r\nThe pancreas has three main regions: the head, body, and tail. The **pancreatic tail** is the leftmost portion of the pancreas and is located in the left upper quadrant of the abdomen. It lies **anterior** (in front of) to the **left kidney**.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Philadelphia, MO: Elsevier; 2020: 332.","responses":[{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sigmoid colon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left kidney","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophagus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right kidney","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3322,"text":"Which of the following types of cells are majorly placed centrally in the pancreas?","explanation":"The pancreas is a gland located in the abdomen, and it plays a crucial role in the regulation of blood glucose levels. It contains various types of cells, each responsible for the secretion of specific hormones. The two major types of cells found in the pancreas are alpha cells and beta cells.\r\n\r\n1. **Alpha cells:** These cells are primarily located in the periphery of the islets of Langerhans in the pancreas. They secrete the hormone glucagon, which helps raise blood glucose levels by promoting the breakdown of glycogen in the liver and the release of glucose into the bloodstream.\r\n\r\n2. **Beta cells:** These cells are centrally placed within the islets of Langerhans in the pancreas. They are responsible for producing and releasing the hormone insulin. Insulin plays a key role in lowering blood glucose levels by facilitating the uptake of glucose by cells, especially in muscles and adipose tissue.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 427.","responses":[{"text":"PP cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Delta cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3328,"text":"Which of the following enzymes is needed to convert norepinephrine to epinephrine?","explanation":"The biosynthesis of epinephrine (adrenaline) from norepinephrine occurs in the adrenal medulla. The conversion is catalyzed by the enzyme **Phenylethanolamine N-methyltransferase (PNMT)**, which transfers a methyl group from S-adenosylmethionine to norepinephrine to form epinephrine.\r\n\r\nThe biosynthetic pathway for the synthesis of epinephrine is as follows:\r\n1. **Tyrosine Hydroxylase:** Converts the amino acid tyrosine to L-DOPA (dihydroxyphenylalanine).\r\n2. **DOPA Decarboxylase:** Converts L-DOPA to dopamine.\r\n3. **Dopamine Beta-Hydroxylase:** Converts dopamine to norepinephrine.\r\n4. **Phenylethanolamine N-methyltransferase (PNMT):** Converts norepinephrine to epinephrine.","reference":"Rodwell VW, Bender DA, Botham KM, Kennelly PJ, Weil PA. Harper’s Illustrated Biochemistry. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 739.","responses":[{"text":"Monoamine oxidase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"DOPA hydroxylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Catechol-O-methyltransferase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phenylethanolamine N-methyltransferase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tyrosine hydroxylase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3333,"text":"Parathyroid hormone, growth hormone-releasing hormone, and glucagon all use which signaling pathway?","explanation":"Parathyroid hormone (PTH), growth hormone-releasing hormone (GHRH), and glucagon are all peptide hormones that act on cell surface receptors and utilize the **cAMP (cyclic adenosine monophosphate) signaling pathway** to exert their effects.\r\n\r\nWhen these hormones bind to their respective receptors on the cell surface, it leads to the activation of a G-protein coupled receptor (GPCR). The activated GPCR then stimulates the production of cAMP from ATP by the enzyme adenylate cyclase. cAMP serves as a second messenger, activating protein kinase A (PKA), which phosphorylates various target proteins in the cell, leading to the cellular response to the hormone.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 924.","responses":[{"text":"cGMP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intracellular receptor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Receptor tyrosine kinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"cAMP","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"IP3","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3338,"text":"What differentiates the pancreas from the parotid gland?","explanation":"The key difference that sets the pancreas apart from the parotid gland is the **presence of centroacinar cells and absence of striated ducts** in the pancreas.\r\n\r\n1. **Centroacinar cells**: These are specialized cells found in the **center of acini** (clusters of secretory cells) in the pancreas. They play an essential role in the production of pancreatic enzymes. These enzymes are initially synthesized in the rough endoplasmic reticulum of acinar cells and are then transported through the centroacinar cells into the pancreatic duct system.\r\n\r\n2. **Striated ducts**: These are a distinctive feature of the parotid gland. Striated ducts have extensive infoldings of the basal cell membrane, which gives them a \"striated\" appearance. They are involved in modifying the primary saliva by reabsorbing sodium and chloride ions and secreting potassium and bicarbonate ions.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 333.","responses":[{"text":"Compound glands are present in the pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Presence of striated ducts in the pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Presence of centroacinar cells and absence of striated ducts in the pancreas","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Serous acini are present in the parotid, not in the pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secretory cells arranged in a circle around a central duct in the pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3358,"text":"What is the most common cause of Addison's disease in the West?","explanation":"Addison's disease, also known as primary adrenal insufficiency, is a condition characterized by the inadequate production of hormones by the adrenal glands. In the Western world, the most common cause of Addison's disease is autoimmune adrenalitis.\r\n\r\n**Autoimmune adrenalitis** occurs when the body's immune system mistakenly attacks and destroys the adrenal glands. This leads to a progressive loss of adrenal function and a decrease in the production of essential hormones, such as cortisol and aldosterone. Over time, the adrenal glands become smaller and may show signs of chronic inflammation.\r\n\r\nWhile tuberculosis used to be a common cause of Addison's disease in the past, particularly in developing countries, it has become less prevalent in the Western world due to improved healthcare and antibiotic treatments. Tumors of the adrenal gland, congenital absence of the adrenal gland, and infections are relatively rare causes of primary adrenal insufficiency compared to autoimmune adrenalitis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1123.","responses":[{"text":"Tumor of adrenal gland","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congenital absence of adrenal gland","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autoimmune adrenalitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3407,"text":"Which of the following causes lead to muscle weakness in Conn syndrome?","explanation":"Conn syndrome, also known as primary hyperaldosteronism, is a disorder characterized by excessive production of aldosterone by the adrenal glands. Aldosterone plays a key role in the regulation of electrolyte balance in the body, particularly the retention of sodium and the excretion of potassium by the kidneys.\r\n\r\nIn Conn syndrome, the excessive aldosterone leads to **increased sodium reabsorption** and **potassium excretion** by the renal tubules. As a result, there is a net loss of potassium from the body, leading to **hypokalemia** (low blood potassium levels).\r\n\r\n**Muscle weakness** is a common clinical manifestation of hypokalemia. Potassium is essential for maintaining proper muscle function, including muscle contraction and relaxation. Low potassium levels disrupt the normal electrical activity of muscle cells, leading to weakness, fatigue, and sometimes even muscle cramps.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 960.","responses":[{"text":"Hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypokalemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypernatremia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypercalcemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neuropathy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3430,"text":"Which of the following secretes androgens?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 956.","responses":[{"text":"Adrenal medulla","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona fasciculata","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona reticularis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona glomerulosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3442,"text":"Which of the following will be seen in mineralocorticoid deficiency?","explanation":"Mineralocorticoids, such as aldosterone, are hormones produced by the adrenal glands that play a crucial role in the regulation of electrolyte balance, particularly sodium (Na) and potassium (K), in the body.\r\n\r\nIn mineralocorticoid deficiency, there is a lack of aldosterone, which leads to impaired reabsorption of sodium in the renal tubules. This results in **decreased reabsorption of Na** by the kidneys, leading to increased urinary excretion of Na. As a consequence, the body loses excess Na, and there is a decrease in extracellular fluid volume (hypovolemia) and blood pressure.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, with decreased aldosterone, there is also **reduced excretion of potassium** in the urine, leading to **hyperkalemia** (elevated blood potassium levels). The lack of aldosterone reduces the secretion of potassium into the urine, resulting in its accumulation in the blood.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 969.","responses":[{"text":"Decrease reabsorption of Na and K","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decrease reabsorption of Na and hyperkalemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Decrease reabsorption of Ca and hypokalemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of them","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase reabsorption of Na","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4877,"text":"Which of the following artery supplies blood to the pancreas?","explanation":"The pancreas receives its blood supply primarily from the **splenic artery**, a branch of the **celiac trunk**. The celiac trunk is a major branch of the abdominal aorta that supplies blood to various organs in the upper abdomen, including the liver, stomach, spleen, and pancreas.\r\n\r\nThe splenic artery courses along the upper border of the pancreas and then divides into multiple smaller branches within the pancreas itself. These branches form an intricate network of blood vessels that supply the various parts of the pancreas.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 491.","responses":[{"text":"Cystic artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior esophageal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left gastric artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior mesenteric artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Splenic artery","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4954,"text":"Which of the following enzymes is responsible for cleaving off glucose-1-phosphate from the peripheral end of a long branch of glycogen during glycogenolysis?","explanation":"**Glycogen phosphorylase** is the enzyme responsible for cleaving off glucose-1-phosphate from the peripheral end of a long branch of glycogen during glycogenolysis. \r\n\r\nGlycogenolysis is the breakdown of glycogen into glucose to provide a rapid source of energy. The process involves the sequential removal of glucose molecules from the non-reducing ends of glycogen branches. Glycogen phosphorylase is a key enzyme involved in this process.\r\n\r\nWhen glycogen phosphorylase acts on the glycogen molecule, it cleaves glucose units from the outermost ends of the glycogen branches by catalyzing the following reaction:\r\n\r\nGlycogen + Phosphate → Glycogen (n-1) + Glucose-1-phosphate\r\n\r\nThis reaction results in the release of glucose-1-phosphate and a smaller glycogen molecule with one less glucose unit. The released glucose-1-phosphate can be further metabolized to provide energy or used for other metabolic processes.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 128.","responses":[{"text":"Glycogen phosphorylase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose-6-phosphatase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Branching enzyme","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Debranching enzyme","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycogen synthase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7418,"text":"What is the role of anti-diuretic hormone in the human body?","explanation":"**Anti-diuretic hormone (ADH)**, also known as vasopressin, plays a crucial role in regulating water balance in the human body.\r\n\r\nADH is produced in the hypothalamus and released by the posterior pituitary gland in response to changes in blood osmolality and blood volume. Its primary function is to regulate water reabsorption in the kidneys and maintain the body's water balance.\r\n\r\nWhen blood osmolality increases (indicating higher solute concentration), or when blood volume decreases (indicating dehydration or reduced blood pressure), the hypothalamus senses these changes and releases ADH into the bloodstream. ADH then acts on the kidneys to increase water reabsorption in the collecting ducts. As a result, less water is excreted in urine, and more water is retained in the body, helping to restore normal blood osmolality and volume.\r\n\r\nConversely, when blood osmolality is low or blood volume is high, ADH secretion decreases, leading to increased water excretion in urine and maintaining proper water balance.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 939.","responses":[{"text":"Helps regulate water balance in the body","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Helps regulate absorption of chloride","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Helps regulate absorption of phosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Helps regulate absorption of potassium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Helps regulate absorption of sodium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8262,"text":"A 30-year-old woman presents to the clinic with palpitations, weight loss, and excessive sweating for almost 5-6 months. She cannot concentrate on carrying out her daily activities especially looking after her children. Recently, she also developed pain in both eyes and her friend told her that one of her eyes has become more prominent than the other. What is the most likely cause of her condition?","explanation":"The patient's symptoms, including palpitations, weight loss, excessive sweating, inability to concentrate, and prominent eyes, are characteristic of **hyperthyroidism**. Grave's disease is an autoimmune disorder where the immune system produces antibodies that stimulate the thyroid gland to produce excessive amounts of thyroid hormones.\r\n\r\nCommon clinical features of Grave's disease include:\r\n\r\n1. **Palpitations**: Due to an increased heart rate and cardiac output caused by elevated thyroid hormones.\r\n\r\n2. **Weight loss**: Hyperthyroidism increases metabolic rate, leading to unintended weight loss.\r\n\r\n3. **Excessive sweating**: Hyperthyroidism increases sympathetic nervous system activity, leading to increased sweating.\r\n\r\n4. **Inability to concentrate**: Excessive thyroid hormones can affect mental function and cause difficulty in focusing.\r\n\r\n5. **Prominent eyes (exophthalmos)**: Grave's disease can lead to swelling of the tissues behind the eyes, causing the eyes to bulge forward.\r\n\r\nThe combination of these symptoms strongly suggests Grave's disease as the underlying cause of her condition.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1081-1082.","responses":[{"text":"Toxic nodular goiter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Generalized anxiety disorder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperthyroidism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hashimoto’s thyroiditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Grave’s disease","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":8656,"text":"What is the marked macrovascular complication of type 2 diabetes mellitus?","explanation":"Type 2 diabetes mellitus is a metabolic disorder characterized by insulin resistance and impaired insulin secretion. It can lead to various complications, both microvascular and macrovascular, due to the chronic hyperglycemia and associated metabolic disturbances.\r\n\r\n**Macrovascular complications** involve large blood vessels and are major contributors to morbidity and mortality in individuals with type 2 diabetes. **Accelerated atherosclerosis** is a significant macrovascular complication observed in diabetes. Atherosclerosis is the buildup of fatty plaques in the arterial walls, leading to narrowing and hardening of the blood vessels.\r\n\r\nIn patients with type 2 diabetes, chronic high blood glucose levels can damage blood vessels and promote the development of atherosclerosis at an accelerated rate. This increases the risk of **coronary artery disease**, **stroke**, and **peripheral vascular disease**.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1107.","responses":[{"text":"Accelerated atherosclerosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Retinal vein occlusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tunnel vision","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diminishing vision","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accelerated arthritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9542,"text":"The pituitary gland is a pea-sized gland that plays a major role in regulating vital body functions and general well-being.  It is referred to as the body's master gland because it controls the activity of most other hormone-secreting glands. What part of the anterior pituitary gland is mainly responsible for hormone secretion?","explanation":"The pituitary gland is a small, pea-sized gland located at the base of the brain. It consists of two main parts: the anterior pituitary (adenohypophysis) and the posterior pituitary (neurohypophysis).\r\n\r\nThe **Pars anterior**  is responsible for the secretion of several important hormones, which play a vital role in regulating various body functions and maintaining general well-being. Some of the hormones secreted by the anterior pituitary include:\r\n\r\n1. **Growth hormone (GH)**: Stimulates growth, protein synthesis, and tissue repair.\r\n\r\n2. **Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH)**: Stimulates the adrenal glands to secrete cortisol, which is involved in the stress response and metabolism.\r\n\r\n3. **Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH)**: Stimulates the thyroid gland to produce thyroid hormones that regulate metabolism.\r\n\r\n4. **Follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH)** and **Luteinizing hormone (LH)**: Regulate the reproductive system and sex hormone production.\r\n\r\n5. **Prolactin (PRL)**: Stimulates milk production in lactating females.\r\n\r\nThe anterior pituitary is under the control of releasing and inhibiting hormones produced in the **hypothalamus**. These hormones travel through the blood vessels connecting the hypothalamus and the anterior pituitary, regulating the secretion of specific hormones.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 929.\r\n(2)Ilahi S, Ilahi TB. Anatomy, adenohypophysis(Pars anterior, anterior pituitary). In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 23, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519039/","responses":[{"text":"Pars anterior","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars intermedia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars tuberalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars nervosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothalamus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9551,"text":"On examining histological slides, the students get confused between the alpha cells and beta cells, forgetting their location in the pancreas. They were informed that the location of alpha cells is in which of the following?","explanation":"The pancreas is a glandular organ with both endocrine and exocrine functions. The endocrine portion of the pancreas consists of clusters of hormone-secreting cells known as islets of Langerhans. These islets contain different types of cells, including alpha cells and beta cells.\r\n\r\n**Alpha cells** are responsible for producing the hormone **glucagon**, which plays a key role in increasing blood glucose levels. These cells are predominantly located towards the **periphery of the islets**. On the other hand, **beta cells** are responsible for producing the hormone **insulin**, which helps in lowering blood glucose levels, and they are mainly found in the **center of the islets**.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 427.","responses":[{"text":"Only in the periphery of islets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Near the periphery of islets","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Equally in both regions of islets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Towards the center of islets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Only in the center of islets","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9557,"text":"Which of the following is the transporter responsible for the transport of iodine into the thyroid cells against the concentration gradient?","explanation":"**Na+/I- symport** is a specific transport mechanism that actively transports **iodine (I-)** into the thyroid cells from the bloodstream, **against the concentration gradient**. This process is coupled with the movement of **sodium ions (Na+)** into the cell, utilizing the electrochemical gradient of sodium. The concentration of iodine inside the thyroid cell is higher than in the surrounding bloodstream, enabling the synthesis of thyroid hormones.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 941.","responses":[{"text":"I-/Cl- antiport","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"K+, I- symport","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Na+, glucose symport","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Na+, I- symport","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9559,"text":"In the process of release of insulin, beta cells of the pancreas get depolarized by which of the following?","explanation":"When blood glucose levels rise, the beta cells of the pancreas respond by releasing insulin to regulate glucose uptake and utilization in the body. The process of insulin release involves a series of events, and depolarization of the beta cells is a critical step.\r\n\r\nWhen glucose enters the beta cells, it undergoes glycolysis and produces ATP. The increased intracellular ATP levels lead to the **ATP-dependent closure of K+ channels**, which prevents the efflux of K+ from the cell. This causes the cell to become depolarized.\r\n\r\nDepolarization opens **voltage-gated Ca2+ channels**, and Ca2+ enters the cell. The increased intracellular Ca2+ triggers the exocytosis of insulin-containing vesicles, leading to the release of insulin into the bloodstream.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 979.","responses":[{"text":"Entry of Na+ by voltage gated channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ATP-dependant opening of K+ channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ATP-dependant closure of Ca2+ channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Entry of Ca2+ by voltage gated channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ATP-dependant closure of K+ channels","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9584,"text":"Glucagon is a peptide hormone. The primary target for glucagon is the liver, where its action is mediated by which of the following second messenger systems?","explanation":"Glucagon is a peptide hormone produced and secreted by the alpha cells of the pancreas. Its primary role is to regulate blood glucose levels. When blood glucose levels are low, glucagon is released to stimulate glucose production and release from the liver into the bloodstream.\r\n\r\n**Glucagon binds to specific receptors on the surface of hepatocytes (liver cells), which activates the enzyme adenylate cyclase. Adenylate cyclase converts ATP to cAMP**, a secondary messenger molecule. cAMP, in turn, activates protein kinase A (PKA), which leads to a series of intracellular events.\r\n\r\nOne of the major effects of PKA activation is the stimulation of glycogenolysis (breakdown of glycogen to release glucose) and gluconeogenesis (production of glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors) in the liver. This raises blood glucose levels, restoring them to normal.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 924.","responses":[{"text":"Nuclear receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"cIMP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"DNA receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"cGMP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"cAMP","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9585,"text":"Hormone secretions from the posterior pituitary include which of the following?","explanation":"The posterior pituitary gland does not synthesize hormones itself; rather, it stores and releases two hormones that are produced by the hypothalamus. These hormones are oxytocin and vasopressin (ADH).\r\n\r\n**1. Oxytocin:** Oxytocin is a peptide hormone that plays a vital role in various reproductive functions. It stimulates uterine contractions during labor and delivery and promotes milk ejection during breastfeeding. Additionally, oxytocin is involved in social bonding and maternal behaviors.\r\n\r\n**2. Vasopressin (ADH):** Vasopressin is an antidiuretic hormone that regulates water balance in the body. It acts on the kidneys, promoting water reabsorption, and reducing urine output. This helps maintain body fluid balance and prevents dehydration.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 917.","responses":[{"text":"Prolactin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxytocin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroxin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Progesterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leptin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9610,"text":"A 30-year-old man presents to the medical outpatient department with complaints of headache for the past 2 days. Pain is moderate in intensity and associated with blurring of vision. On examination, he has a blood pressure of 160/90 mmHg and body mass index (BMI) of 30 kg/m^2. Which of the following is required to fulfill the definition of metabolic syndrome?","explanation":"**The diagnosis of metabolic syndrome requires the presence of at least three of the following five criteria:**\r\n\r\n1. **Impaired fasting glucose:** This means fasting blood sugar levels are higher than normal but not high enough to be diagnosed as diabetes.\r\n\r\n2. **Increased triglyceride levels:** High levels of triglycerides in the blood.\r\n\r\n3. **Decreased HDL cholesterol:** Low levels of \"good\" HDL cholesterol.\r\n\r\n4. **Raised blood pressure:** Hypertension, with systolic blood pressure of 130 mmHg or higher, or diastolic blood pressure of 85 mmHg or higher.\r\n\r\n5. **Central obesity (increased BMI):** Defined as a body mass index (BMI) of 30 kg/m² or higher.\r\n\r\nIn the given scenario, the patient has an elevated BMI (30 kg/m²) along with hypertension (blood pressure of 160/90 mmHg), which meets two criteria for metabolic syndrome. However, the information provided is not sufficient to determine if the patient meets the other criteria.\r\n\r\n**The following additional information is required to fulfill the definition of metabolic syndrome:**\r\n\r\n- Fasting blood glucose levels\r\n- Triglyceride levels\r\n- HDL cholesterol levels","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1103.","responses":[{"text":"Presence of acanthosis nigricans","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"History of using corticosteroids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Impaired fasting glucose, increased triglycerides, decreased HDL","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Impaired fasting glucose, increased triglycerides, decreased HDL, raised uric acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Raised cholesterol and LDL","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10322,"text":"A 54-year-old, married woman para-2 comes to the clinic with the complaint of weight gain and lethargy for the past 3 months. She had her last menstrual period 6 years back. Her blood pressure is 150/90 mmHg, her pulse is 65/min, and is regular bilaterally. Her body mass index (BMI) falls in the obese range. Her eyes are puffy, she complains of breathlessness, and cold intolerance, her skin is coarse and her abdomen has white striations present. What is the best diagnostic test for this woman?","explanation":"The best diagnostic test for this 54-year-old woman is **serum TSH level**. Her clinical presentation is highly suggestive of hypothyroidism. The symptoms of weight gain, lethargy, cold intolerance, puffy eyes, and coarse skin are typical features of hypothyroidism. Additionally, her blood pressure is elevated, which can be seen in hypothyroidism.\r\n\r\nIn this case, measuring the serum TSH level is crucial because an elevated TSH level along with low levels of thyroid hormones (T3 and T4) would confirm the diagnosis of primary hypothyroidism. Primary hypothyroidism is the most common cause of hypothyroidism and is characterized by inadequate thyroid hormone production due to dysfunction of the thyroid gland itself.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 1086.","responses":[{"text":"Serum TSH level","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral glucose tolerance test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum cortisol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum cortisol and TSH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral glucose tolerance test and TSH","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11131,"text":"Which of the following hormones does not use cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) as a second messenger?","explanation":"**Estrogen** is the hormone that does not use **cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP)** as a second messenger.\r\n\r\nHormones that use cAMP as a second messenger belong to the class of **peptide hormones or protein hormones**. When these hormones bind to their specific receptors on the cell surface, it activates the receptor, leading to the generation of cAMP inside the cell. cAMP then acts as a second messenger, activating protein kinases and initiating various intracellular signaling cascades.\r\n\r\nHowever, **estrogen** is a **steroid hormone**, and it uses a different mechanism for signal transduction. Steroid hormones like estrogen are lipophilic and can cross the cell membrane to bind to intracellular receptors located in the cytoplasm or nucleus. This hormone-receptor complex then directly interacts with specific DNA sequences, regulating gene expression and protein synthesis within the target cells.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 924.","responses":[{"text":"Follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucagon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Estrogen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Luteinizing hormone (LH)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcitonin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11137,"text":"When does the thyroid gland come in front of the trachea during development?","explanation":"The thyroid gland comes in front of the trachea during development in the **7th week** of gestation. At this stage, the thyroid gland starts to develop from an endodermal thickening in the floor of the primitive pharynx known as the thyroid diverticulum. It then descends anteriorly and migrates down the neck until it reaches its final position in front of the trachea.\r\n\r\nDuring the **3rd week**, the thyroid diverticulum begins to form, and by the **5th month**, the gland becomes functional, secreting thyroid hormones that play a crucial role in fetal development and growth. However, it's the **7th week** when the thyroid gland becomes visible as a small bud in front of the trachea.\r\n\r\nAfter birth, the thyroid gland continues to grow and develop, and it remains located in the front of the trachea throughout life.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 169.","responses":[{"text":"7th week","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"During fetal period","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3rd week","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"At birth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5th month","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11155,"text":"Which hormone is involved in the ejection of milk from mammary glands during lactation?","explanation":"During lactation, the hormone responsible for the ejection of milk from the mammary glands is **oxytocin**. Oxytocin is produced in the hypothalamus and released from the posterior pituitary gland in response to stimulation of the nipples during breastfeeding.\r\n\r\nWhen a baby suckles at the breast, nerve signals are transmitted to the hypothalamus, which then triggers the release of oxytocin. Oxytocin acts on the myoepithelial cells surrounding the milk-producing mammary gland alveoli. It causes these cells to contract, leading to the ejection of milk into the ducts and eventually out of the nipple, making it available for the baby to feed.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, **prolactin** is another hormone involved in lactation. It is also produced in the pituitary gland and stimulates the production of milk in the mammary glands. Prolactin is responsible for initiating and maintaining milk production, while oxytocin is responsible for milk ejection.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 940.","responses":[{"text":"Glucagon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prolactin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxytocin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatomammotropin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11157,"text":"A 30-year-old patient presents with anorexia after suffering from a head trauma one week ago. Which hypothalamic nucleus is involved in the regulation of thirst and hunger?","explanation":"The **lateral nucleus** of the hypothalamus is involved in the regulation of both thirst and hunger.\r\n\r\n1. **Thirst Regulation:** The lateral hypothalamic area contains neurons that are responsible for triggering thirst sensations. When the body's water levels are low or when there is an increase in the concentration of solutes in the blood, these neurons are activated, leading to the sensation of thirst. Thirst is an essential mechanism that helps maintain proper water balance in the body.\r\n\r\n2. **Hunger Regulation:** The lateral hypothalamic area also plays a significant role in the regulation of hunger. Neurons in this region are involved in stimulating appetite and food intake. When these neurons are activated, it leads to feelings of hunger and an increased desire to eat.","reference":"Castro DC, Cole SL, Berridge KC. Lateral hypothalamus, nucleus accumbens, and ventral pallidum roles in eating and hunger: interactions between homeostatic and reward circuitry. Frontiers in Systems Neuroscience. Published June 15, 2015. Accessed June 24, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4466441/","responses":[{"text":"Posterior nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral nucleus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11162,"text":"Iodine transport in follicular cells of the thyroid gland is an example of which type of transport?","explanation":"Iodine transport in the follicular cells of the thyroid gland is an example of **secondary active transport**. This process involves the movement of iodine against its concentration gradient, from the bloodstream into the thyroid follicular cells. Secondary active transport utilizes the energy stored in the sodium gradient, which is established by primary active transport (specifically, the sodium-potassium ATPase pump). The sodium gradient provides the driving force for the symport of iodine and sodium through a specific transporter located on the basolateral membrane of the follicular cells.\r\n\r\nAs sodium ions move down their concentration gradient into the cell, they bring iodine along with them against its concentration gradient. Once inside the follicular cells, iodine is utilized in the synthesis of thyroid hormones—triiodothyronine (T3) and thyroxine (T4). These hormones play crucial roles in regulating metabolism, growth, and development throughout the body.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 942.","responses":[{"text":"Simple diffusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary active transport","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facilitated diffusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary active transport","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11173,"text":"A person is diagnosed with hypothyroidism and goiter. Her laboratory tests most likely show which of the following?","explanation":"Hypothyroidism is a condition characterized by an underactive thyroid gland, leading to low levels of thyroid hormones (T3 and T4) in the blood. It often presents with an enlarged thyroid gland, known as a goiter.\r\n\r\nIn primary hypothyroidism, the problem lies within the thyroid gland itself, resulting in decreased production of T3 and T4. When the thyroid hormone levels in the blood are low, the hypothalamus releases thyrotropin-releasing hormone (TRH), which stimulates the anterior pituitary gland to secrete thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH). TSH, in turn, stimulates the thyroid gland to produce more T3 and T4.\r\n\r\nTherefore, in hypothyroidism with goiter, the laboratory tests are likely to show:\r\n\r\n1. **Increased TSH:** The anterior pituitary gland produces more TSH to try and stimulate the thyroid gland to produce more thyroid hormones.\r\n\r\n2. **Decreased T3 and T4:** Due to the underactive thyroid gland, the levels of T3 and T4 are reduced.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1078.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased TSH and decreased T3, T4","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased TSH and decreased T3, T4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased TSH and increased T3, T4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased TSH and increased T3, T4","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11208,"text":"A histology slide showed a section of tissue containing chromaffin cells with abundant fairly\r\nelectron-dense and moderately electron-dense granules. The tissue corresponds to what section of the adrenal gland?","explanation":"The histology slide showing chromaffin cells with abundant fairly electron-dense and moderately electron-dense granules corresponds to the **medulla** of the adrenal gland.\r\n\r\nThe adrenal gland has two main components: the outer cortex and the inner medulla. The cortex is further divided into three zones, namely zona glomerulosa, zona fasciculata, and zona reticularis. Each zone of the cortex produces different steroid hormones, such as aldosterone, cortisol, and sex hormones.\r\n\r\nThe medulla, on the other hand, is responsible for producing catecholamines, including adrenaline (epinephrine) and noradrenaline (norepinephrine). These hormones are stored in chromaffin cells, which contain abundant granules that appear fairly electron-dense and moderately electron-dense on histological slides.\r\n\r\nThe presence of chromaffin cells with these characteristic granules in the tissue section confirms that it corresponds to the medulla of the adrenal gland.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 425.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona fasciculata","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona glomerulosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medulla","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona reticularis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12496,"text":"Which of the following nuclei of the hypothalamus secrete oxytocin?","explanation":"The **paraventricular nucleus** (PVN) of the hypothalamus is responsible for secreting **oxytocin**. Oxytocin is a peptide hormone produced by the PVN's neurosecretory cells and is stored in the **posterior pituitary gland** for release.\r\n\r\nWhen certain stimuli are received, such as uterine distension during childbirth or stimulation of the breasts during breastfeeding, nerve impulses from these sensory receptors are transmitted to the PVN. This results in the release of oxytocin into the bloodstream.\r\n\r\nOxytocin plays a crucial role in various physiological processes, including:\r\n\r\n1. **Uterine Contractions:** During childbirth, oxytocin stimulates powerful uterine contractions, facilitating labor and delivery.\r\n\r\n2. **Breast Milk Ejection:** Oxytocin promotes the ejection of milk from the mammary glands into the milk ducts, allowing for breastfeeding.\r\n\r\n3. **Social Bonding:** Oxytocin is involved in social bonding and maternal-infant attachment.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 746.","responses":[{"text":"Preoptic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suprachiasmatic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paraventricular","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Arcuate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Supraoptic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12497,"text":"Which of the following structures is responsible for releasing a hormone that regulates blood levels of phosphate and calcium?","explanation":"The structure responsible for regulating blood levels of phosphate and calcium is the **parathyroid gland**. The parathyroid gland is a small endocrine gland located near the thyroid gland in the neck.\r\n\r\nThe parathyroid gland produces and releases the **parathyroid hormone (PTH)**, which plays a key role in maintaining the balance of calcium and phosphate in the blood. PTH acts on various target tissues to increase blood calcium levels and decrease blood phosphate levels. Here's how it works:\r\n\r\n1. **Bone:** PTH stimulates bone resorption, which releases calcium into the blood.\r\n\r\n2. **Kidneys:** PTH enhances the reabsorption of calcium in the kidneys, reducing its excretion in the urine. Additionally, PTH inhibits the reabsorption of phosphate in the kidneys, leading to increased phosphate excretion.\r\n\r\n3. **Intestines:** PTH indirectly increases calcium absorption in the intestines through its action on vitamin D metabolism. It stimulates the activation of vitamin D, which, in turn, enhances calcium absorption in the intestines.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 999.","responses":[{"text":"Parathyroid gland","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid gland","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenal gland","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thymus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior pituitary gland","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12501,"text":"A histologist observed a slide in which cells were arranged in cords around fenestrated capillaries. Some cells were acidic, others were basic, and some didn't take up any stain. Which part of the pituitary gland he must be observing?","explanation":"The histologist is observing the **Pars distalis** of the pituitary gland.\r\n\r\nThe pituitary gland is divided into two main parts: the anterior pituitary (adenohypophysis) and the posterior pituitary (neurohypophysis). The Pars distalis is the largest and most prominent part of the anterior pituitary, where the majority of hormone-secreting cells are located.\r\n\r\nThe cords of cells observed in the Pars distalis are organized around fenestrated capillaries, forming a distinctive histological pattern. These cells are known as **acidophilic**, **basophilic**, and **chromophobe cells**. Acidophilic cells stain with acidic dyes and secrete hormones like growth hormone (GH) and prolactin (PRL). Basophilic cells stain with basic dyes and produce hormones like adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) and thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH). Chromophobe cells do not take up stains well and represent non-functional or degranulated cells.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 152.","responses":[{"text":"Pars distalis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Infundibulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars tuberalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenohypophysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neurohypophysis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12503,"text":"A histologist observed a slide consisting of basophilic polygonal cells called melanotrophs. Which part of the pituitary gland he must be observing?","explanation":"The histologist is likely observing the **pars intermedia** of the pituitary gland. The pituitary gland, also known as the **hypophysis**, is divided into two main parts: the **neurohypophysis** (posterior pituitary) and the **adenohypophysis** (anterior pituitary), separated by the **pars intermedia**.\r\n\r\nThe **pars intermedia** is a thin layer of basophilic polygonal cells located between the anterior and posterior lobes of the pituitary gland. It is involved in the production and secretion of **melanocyte-stimulating hormone (MSH)**.\r\n\r\n**Melanotrophs** are specialized cells found in the **pars intermedia** that produce and store MSH. MSH is responsible for stimulating the production and release of melanin pigment in melanocytes, the cells that give color to the skin, hair, and eyes.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 153.","responses":[{"text":"Pars intermedia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars distalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neurohypophysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infundibulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars tuberalis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12504,"text":"Which of the following substances is stored in the herring bodies of the pars nervosa?","explanation":"The **herring bodies** are specialized structures found in the **pars nervosa** (posterior pituitary) of the pituitary gland. These structures are actually **dilated axon terminals** of hypothalamic neurons that extend from the **hypothalamus** into the posterior pituitary. The herring bodies serve as **storage sites** for **neurosecretory material**, which includes the hormones produced by these hypothalamic neurons.\r\n\r\nThe two main hormones stored in the herring bodies are:\r\n\r\n1. **Oxytocin:** Oxytocin is a peptide hormone that plays a crucial role in uterine contractions during childbirth and milk ejection during breastfeeding. It is also involved in social bonding and maternal behaviors.\r\n\r\n2. **Antidiuretic Hormone (ADH) or Vasopressin:** ADH is a peptide hormone that regulates water balance by promoting water reabsorption in the kidneys. It helps conserve water and concentrates urine when the body is dehydrated.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 154.","responses":[{"text":"Residual material","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hormones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neurosecretory material","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Enzymes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amorphous material","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12617,"text":"Which one of the following classifications best fits the nature of pancreatic secretions?","explanation":"The nature of pancreatic secretions is **mixed**, meaning it contains both exocrine and endocrine components. The pancreas is a vital organ with dual functions: it serves as both an exocrine gland and an endocrine gland.\r\n\r\n1. **Exocrine Function:** The majority of the pancreas is composed of exocrine tissue, which secretes digestive enzymes into the pancreatic ducts. These enzymes, such as amylase, lipase, and proteases, are essential for breaking down carbohydrates, fats, and proteins in the small intestine, aiding in the digestion and absorption of nutrients.\r\n\r\n2. **Endocrine Function:** Scattered throughout the exocrine tissue are small clusters of cells called **islets of Langerhans**, which constitute the endocrine portion of the pancreas. These islets contain different cell types, including alpha cells that produce glucagon, beta cells that produce insulin, and delta cells that produce somatostatin. These hormones are released directly into the bloodstream and play crucial roles in regulating blood glucose levels and metabolism.","reference":"Endocrinology module; Histology lecture slides; Topic: Microscopic structure of the pancreas; Sub-topic: Histological components of the pancreas.","responses":[{"text":"Purely endocrine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mixed","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Purely exocrine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Purely mucous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Purely serous","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12618,"text":"Which one of the following is the special type of vessel found around endocrine glands?","explanation":"The special type of vessel found around endocrine glands is **continuous fenestrated capillaries**. These capillaries are characterized by having small fenestrations or pores in their endothelial cells. These fenestrations allow for the rapid exchange of small molecules and fluid between the blood and the surrounding tissues.\r\n\r\nEndocrine glands secrete hormones directly into the bloodstream. To facilitate the efficient release and distribution of hormones, they are surrounded by a dense network of continuous fenestrated capillaries. These capillaries provide an extensive surface area for hormone exchange between the glandular cells and the bloodstream.","reference":"Godwin L, Tariq MA, Crane JS. Histology, Capillary. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed November 23, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK546578/","responses":[{"text":"Venules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Discontinuous capillaries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arterioles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Continuous fenestrated capillaries","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Discontinuous fenestrated capillaries","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12622,"text":"Which one of the following gives rise to the ventral and dorsal pancreatic buds?","explanation":"During embryonic development, the pancreas originates from the **endodermal germ layer**. The formation of the pancreas involves two buds known as the **ventral pancreatic bud** and the **dorsal pancreatic bud**. These buds develop from the **endoderm**.\r\n\r\nThe process of pancreas development begins with the formation of a diverticulum from the foregut endoderm, which is the initial stage of the gastrointestinal tract. The diverticulum elongates and undergoes branching morphogenesis to form two buds: the ventral pancreatic bud and the dorsal pancreatic bud.\r\n\r\nThe ventral pancreatic bud arises from the bile duct, which is an outgrowth of the hepatic diverticulum. The dorsal pancreatic bud arises separately from the dorsal side of the duodenum, which is a part of the foregut endoderm.\r\n\r\nThe two buds eventually fuse together and continue to differentiate to form the complete pancreas. The ventral bud primarily contributes to the formation of the head and uncinate process of the pancreas, while the dorsal bud gives rise to the body, tail, and isthmus.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia M. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 9th ed. Elsevier; 2011: 223.","responses":[{"text":"Endoderm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ectoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoderm of the esophagus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesenchyme","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12624,"text":"The ectopic pancreas can be seen at which of the following locations of the body?","explanation":"**Ectopic pancreas**, also known as pancreatic rest, heterotopic pancreas, or accessory pancreas, is a rare condition where pancreatic tissue is found in locations outside the normal pancreas. One of the common locations for ectopic pancreas is the **gastric antrum**.\r\n\r\nDuring embryonic development, the pancreas forms from two buds: the ventral bud and the dorsal bud. Aberrations during this process can lead to ectopic pancreatic tissue appearing in various locations. In the case of gastric antrum ectopic pancreas, pancreatic tissue is found within the wall of the stomach, particularly in the lower part called the antrum.\r\n\r\nEctopic pancreatic tissue in the gastric antrum typically exhibits the same histological features as the normal pancreas, including acinar cells, ducts, and islet cells. In most instances, ectopic pancreas in the gastric antrum is asymptomatic and discovered incidentally during imaging or endoscopy.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia M. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 9th ed. Elsevier; 2011.: 225.","responses":[{"text":"Rectum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric antrum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Colon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trachea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophagus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12634,"text":"A patient comes to the outpatient department complaining of swelling in front of the neck. After examination and investigation, a diagnosis of the enlarged thyroid gland was made. Which of the following structures gives rise to the enlarged gland?","explanation":"The enlarged thyroid gland is derived from the **endodermal cells of the primitive pharynx** during embryonic development. The thyroid gland originates from two main structures: the median endodermal thickening known as the thyroid diverticulum and the **dorsal bud**.\r\n\r\nThe thyroid diverticulum arises from the floor of the primitive pharynx and forms an endodermal outpouching. It descends anteriorly in the neck to give rise to the thyroid primordium. The thyroid diverticulum migrates downward, passing through the developing hyoid bone and laryngeal cartilages until it reaches its final position in front of the trachea, just below the laryngeal prominence (Adam's apple).\r\n\r\nMeanwhile, the **dorsal bud**, an outgrowth from the fourth pharyngeal pouch, contributes to the formation of the ultimobranchial body, which gives rise to the parafollicular (C) cells of the thyroid gland.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia M. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 9th ed. Elsevier; 2011: 173.","responses":[{"text":"Ruthke's pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endodermal cells of primitive pharynx","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"3rd pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"First pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsal bud","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12659,"text":"On which of the following structures does the growth hormone exert its function indirectly through IGF-1?","explanation":"The growth hormone (GH) exerts its function indirectly through insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1), which is also known as somatomedin C. After being released from the anterior pituitary gland, GH stimulates the production and secretion of IGF-1 in various tissues, primarily in the liver.\r\n\r\nIGF-1 plays a crucial role in mediating the growth-promoting effects of GH. It acts on target tissues, including skeletal muscle, adipose tissue, and **chondrocytes in the epiphyseal cartilage** of long bones.\r\n\r\nIn the epiphyseal plates, chondrocytes are responsible for longitudinal bone growth during childhood and adolescence. IGF-1 stimulates these chondrocytes, promoting their proliferation and maturation, which leads to the lengthening of long bones.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 935.","responses":[{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac muscles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chondrocytes in epiphyseal cartilage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Skeletal muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adipose tissue","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12660,"text":"Which of the following statements accurately states the action of growth hormone on metabolism?","explanation":"One of the primary metabolic actions of growth hormone is to **increase the use of fatty acids for energy production**. GH promotes lipolysis, the breakdown of stored triglycerides in adipose tissue, leading to the release of free fatty acids into the bloodstream. These fatty acids are then taken up by various tissues, especially muscle cells, and are utilized as an energy source during periods of fasting or increased energy demands.\r\n\r\nGrowth hormone has **anti-insulin-like effects**, meaning it opposes some of the actions of insulin. It can lead to increased blood glucose levels and decreased glucose uptake by certain tissues.\r\n\r\nWhile GH does play a role in carbohydrate metabolism, its prominent effect is on **stimulating lipolysis and increasing the use of fatty acids** as an energy source.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 934.","responses":[{"text":"Inhibition of insulin like growth factor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increasing the usage of carbohydrates","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreasing the rate of photosynthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreasing the mobilization of fats from adipose tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increasing use of fatty acids for energy production","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12717,"text":"The antidiuretic hormone stimulates the movement of which of the following intracellular protein to the luminal side of the collecting tubules?","explanation":"The antidiuretic hormone (ADH), also known as vasopressin, plays a crucial role in regulating water balance in the body. One of its main targets is the **aquaporin-2 (AQP2)** water channel protein in the collecting ducts of the kidneys.\r\n\r\nWhen ADH is released in response to increased plasma osmolality or decreased blood volume, it binds to its receptor on the basolateral membrane of the principal cells in the collecting ducts. This binding activates a cAMP-mediated signaling pathway that leads to the **insertion of AQP2 channels into the apical/luminal membrane** of these cells. As a result, AQP2 channels facilitate the reabsorption of water from the tubular fluid back into the cells and then into the interstitium, reducing urine output and conserving water in the body.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 359.","responses":[{"text":"Aquaporin-5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aquaporin-2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aquaporin-1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aquaporin-4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aquaporin-3","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12719,"text":"A 29-year-old man complains of weight gain, constipation, decreased energy, lethargy, and dry skin for the past 6 months. He was diagnosed with hypothyroidism and was put on synthetic thyroid hormone therapy. A decrease in which of the following hormonal levels should be observed to find if the treatment is effective?","explanation":"**Thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH)**is produced by the anterior pituitary gland and acts on the thyroid gland to stimulate the synthesis and release of thyroid hormones (T4 and T3). In hypothyroidism, the TSH levels are usually elevated as the body tries to compensate for the lack of thyroid hormones. When the patient is put on synthetic thyroid hormone therapy and the treatment is effective, the TSH levels should decrease to normal or low levels. This indicates that the thyroid hormones are being adequately replaced, and the pituitary gland does not need to produce excess TSH.\r\n\r\nMonitoring free T4 and free T3 levels is also important, as they reflect the levels of active thyroid hormones in the bloodstream. However, TSH is considered the most sensitive and specific marker for assessing the effectiveness of hypothyroidism treatment.","reference":"Shahid MA, Ashraf MA, Sharma S. Physiology, thyroid hormone. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed November 26, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK500006/","responses":[{"text":"Vitamin A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Free T4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid stimulating hormone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma iron","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma cholesterol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Free T3","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12720,"text":"Lab investigations of a 35-year-old woman revealed low serum levels of thyroxine, and serum level of thyroid-stimulating hormones was also down but a rapid increase in TSH level was seen when given a synthetic thyroid releasing factor. Which of the following can be the reason for her hypothyroidism?","explanation":"The condition described in the 35-year-old woman with low serum levels of thyroxine (T4) and decreased thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH), but a rapid increase in TSH when given a synthetic thyroid-releasing factor, points towards a **secondary hypothyroidism**.\r\n\r\n**Correct Answer: Hypothalamus**\r\n\r\nIn secondary hypothyroidism, the dysfunction lies in the hypothalamus, specifically in the hypothalamic-pituitary axis. The hypothalamus normally secretes thyrotropin-releasing hormone (TRH), which stimulates the anterior pituitary gland to produce and release thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH). TSH, in turn, stimulates the thyroid gland to produce and release thyroid hormones (T4 and T3). However, in this case, there is a problem with the hypothalamus, leading to reduced secretion of TRH, which results in decreased TSH production and subsequently decreased thyroid hormone synthesis.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 952.","responses":[{"text":"Posterior pituitary","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid receptor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid follicles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothalamus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior pituitary","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12721,"text":"Which of the following is the action of parathyroid to rapidly increase serum calcium levels?","explanation":"When blood calcium levels decrease, the parathyroid glands release PTH. PTH acts on the kidneys to increase calcium reabsorption in the **distal convoluted tubules**. This action prevents the loss of calcium in the urine, leading to increased retention of calcium in the bloodstream.\r\n\r\nThe proximal convoluted tubules primarily reabsorb **phosphate** from the glomerular filtrate, not calcium. In cases of hypocalcemia, the reabsorption of phosphate in the proximal tubules is actually decreased due to PTH's effect, which helps to maintain calcium-phosphate balance in the body.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1001.","responses":[{"text":"Calcium and phosphate absorption from the entire nephron","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium from distal convoluted tubules","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphate from proximal convoluted tubules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium from proximal convoluted tubules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphate from distal convoluted tubule","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12722,"text":"Vitamin D acts on the intestinal epithelial cells to help form which of the following proteins to increase calcium absorption from the intestine?","explanation":"**Calbindin** is a calcium-binding protein present in the enterocytes (intestinal epithelial cells). When vitamin D binds to its receptor in the enterocytes, it induces the synthesis of calbindin. Calbindin facilitates the transcellular transport of calcium across the intestinal epithelium.\r\n\r\nThe process of calcium absorption involves two main pathways: paracellular and transcellular. Paracellular transport involves the passive movement of calcium through tight junctions between enterocytes. Transcellular transport, on the other hand, involves active transport of calcium across the enterocyte, which is enhanced by calbindin.\r\n\r\nBy increasing the expression of calbindin, vitamin D enhances the efficiency of transcellular calcium absorption, leading to increased calcium uptake from the intestine into the bloodstream.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 999.","responses":[{"text":"Calcineurin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calbindin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Calsequestrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcitonin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calmodulin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12724,"text":"In a laboratory experiment, it was observed that oral glucose administration results in a much larger increase in serum insulin levels than intravenous glucose administration. Which one of the following hormones causes this effect?","explanation":"**Gastrin dependent insulinotropic peptide (GIP)**, also known as glucose-dependent insulinotropic peptide, is an incretin hormone secreted by the enteroendocrine K cells in the small intestine in response to oral glucose intake. It plays a significant role in enhancing insulin secretion from beta cells in the pancreas.\r\n\r\nWhen glucose is ingested orally, it stimulates the release of GIP from the intestinal K cells. GIP then enters the bloodstream and travels to the pancreas, where it acts as an incretin hormone. Incretin hormones like GIP potentiate the insulin response to oral glucose. They stimulate beta cells to release more insulin and promote glucose uptake in peripheral tissues, resulting in a more substantial increase in serum insulin levels and better glucose clearance after meals.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 792.","responses":[{"text":"Glucagon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatostatin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leptin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastrin dependent insulinotropic peptide","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12796,"text":"During hyperglycemia, blood glucose enters the beta cells of the pancreas by which of the following glucose transporter?","explanation":"**GLUT-2** (Glucose Transporter-2) is a high-capacity, low-affinity glucose transporter that is abundantly expressed in beta cells of the pancreas. It plays a vital role in the regulation of insulin secretion. GLUT-2 has a low affinity for glucose, allowing beta cells to sense variations in extracellular glucose levels. When blood glucose levels are high, GLUT-2 facilitates the entry of glucose into the beta cells, triggering insulin secretion in response to hyperglycemia.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 979.","responses":[{"text":"GLUT-4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT-5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT-1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT-3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT-2","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12813,"text":"In the United States, people fast for nearly 20 hours in the month of Ramadan in the summer. which one of the following metabolic processes maintains blood glucose levels during this period?","explanation":"**Glycogenolysis** is the breakdown of glycogen, which is the stored form of glucose in the liver and muscle cells. During fasting, the body initially uses the stored glycogen to provide glucose for energy. The liver, in particular, plays a crucial role in releasing glucose through glycogenolysis to maintain blood glucose levels between meals.\r\n\r\nAs fasting continues and glycogen stores are depleted, other processes like gluconeogenesis (the synthesis of glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors) also come into play to sustain blood glucose levels.","reference":"Sanvictores T, Casale J, Huecker MR. Physiology, fasting. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed December 3, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534877/","responses":[{"text":"Glycogenolysis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycogen synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Protein synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gluconeogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Triglyceride synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12836,"text":"Which of the following results will the reports show in a 35-year-old patient taking pharmacological doses of steroidal antiinflammatory drugs for asthma?","explanation":"Pharmacological doses of corticosteroids can have suppressive effects on the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis. Corticosteroids can directly inhibit the production of corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH) in the hypothalamus. CRH is responsible for stimulating the release of adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) from the pituitary gland. When CRH levels are low, there is reduced stimulation of the adrenal glands, leading to decreased production of ACTH. However, the administration of exogenous corticosteroids can result in higher than normal cortisol levels despite low CRH and ACTH levels. This is because the exogenous steroids directly replace the function of cortisol in the body.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 967.","responses":[{"text":"High ACTH, low cortisol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High CRH, low cortisol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low CRH, high cortisol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"High CRH, high cortisol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low CRH, low cortisol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12839,"text":"A 45-year-old male was diagnosed with adrenal diabetes as a result of high serum levels of cortisol due to hypersecretion of the adrenocorticotrophic hormone. Which of the following is associated with the above mentioned condition?","explanation":"Adrenal diabetes, also known as **steroid diabetes** or **corticosteroid-induced diabetes**, is a condition characterized by high blood glucose levels (hyperglycemia) resulting from chronic exposure to high levels of cortisol due to hypersecretion of adrenocorticotrophic hormone (ACTH). This condition can occur as a side effect of prolonged corticosteroid therapy or in individuals with conditions such as Cushing's syndrome.\r\n\r\nThe correct option associated with adrenal diabetes is:\r\n\r\n**Decreased sensitivity of insulin in skeletal muscle cells**\r\n\r\nChronic exposure to high levels of cortisol can lead to insulin resistance, particularly in skeletal muscle cells. Insulin resistance refers to a condition where cells become less responsive to the action of insulin, leading to decreased uptake of glucose from the bloodstream. As a result, blood glucose levels remain elevated despite the presence of insulin.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 963.","responses":[{"text":"Enhanced deposition of fatty acids in adipose tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Absence of beta cells of pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased sensitivity of insulin in skeletal muscle cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Decrease in blood glucose level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enhanced utilization of glucose by cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12868,"text":"A number of structures open (related) in the 2nd part of the duodenum. Which of the following does not have an opening in the duodenum?","explanation":"In the second part of the duodenum, several structures open or empty their contents. The duodenum is the first part of the small intestine and is responsible for receiving and digesting partially digested food from the stomach.\r\n\r\nThe structures that have openings in the second part of the duodenum include:\r\n\r\n1. **Bile Duct:** The bile duct carries bile from the liver and gallbladder to the duodenum, where bile aids in the digestion of fats.\r\n\r\n2. **Pancreatic Duct:** The main pancreatic duct delivers pancreatic enzymes and bicarbonate to the duodenum, assisting in the digestion of carbohydrates, proteins, and fats.\r\n\r\n3. **Accessory Pancreatic Duct:** The accessory pancreatic duct (Duct of Santorini) is an additional duct of the pancreas that may be present in some individuals. It opens into the duodenum at a more proximal location called the minor duodenal papilla.\r\n\r\n4. **Ampulla of Vater:** The ampulla of Vater is the confluence of the bile duct and pancreatic duct, and it opens into the second part of the duodenum through the major duodenal papilla. It allows both bile and pancreatic secretions to enter the duodenum.\r\n\r\nHowever, the **Cystic Duct** does not open into the duodenum. Instead, it connects the gallbladder to the common bile duct, allowing the gallbladder to store and concentrate bile.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 336.","responses":[{"text":"Pancreatic duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystic duct","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bile duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accessory pancreatic duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ampulla of Vater","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12892,"text":"Which of the following function do amino acids mobilized by glucocorticoids play?","explanation":"One of the key metabolic effects of glucocorticoids is their ability to promote **gluconeogenesis**. Gluconeogenesis is the process by which new glucose is synthesized from non-carbohydrate precursors, such as amino acids and glycerol. This is particularly important during fasting or prolonged stress when blood glucose levels need to be maintained to support energy-demanding processes.\r\n\r\nGlucocorticoids stimulate the breakdown of proteins in various tissues, leading to the release of **amino acids** into the bloodstream. These mobilized amino acids serve as substrates for gluconeogenesis in the liver, where they are converted into glucose.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 962.","responses":[{"text":"Ketogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gluconeogenesis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Protein synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycogenolysis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12898,"text":"Glucagon binds to the high-affinity receptors located on the cell membranes of hepatocytes to activate which of the following for a phosphorylation cascade?","explanation":"**Glucagon** is a peptide hormone secreted by the **alpha cells** of the **pancreatic islets** in response to low blood glucose levels. It plays a critical role in regulating glucose homeostasis and promoting glucose release from the liver.\r\n\r\nUpon binding to its specific **high-affinity receptors** located on the **cell membranes** of **hepatocytes** (liver cells), glucagon activates a signaling pathway involving the second messenger **Cyclic AMP (cAMP)**.\r\n\r\nWhen glucagon binds to its receptor, it stimulates the activation of **adenylyl cyclase**, an enzyme that converts **ATP** (adenosine triphosphate) into cAMP. Increased cAMP levels act as a second messenger, initiating a **phosphorylation cascade** by activating **protein kinase A (PKA)**.\r\n\r\nPKA then phosphorylates several target proteins involved in hepatic glucose metabolism. This phosphorylation cascade ultimately leads to the activation of enzymes involved in **glycogenolysis** (breakdown of glycogen into glucose) and **gluconeogenesis** (production of glucose from non-carbohydrate sources), promoting glucose release into the bloodstream.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 982.","responses":[{"text":"Cyclic AMP","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyclic ATP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphodiesterase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inositol trisphosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyclic GMP","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12913,"text":"Which of the following functions of glucose is activated in the absence of insulin?","explanation":"In the absence of insulin, such as during fasting or in insulin-deficient conditions like type 1 diabetes, several metabolic functions are activated as a compensatory mechanism to maintain energy balance.\r\n\r\nOne of these functions is **ketogenesis**. Ketogenesis is the process by which **ketone bodies** (acetoacetate, beta-hydroxybutyrate, and acetone) are produced in the liver from fatty acids. These ketone bodies can serve as an alternative fuel source for tissues, particularly the brain, during periods of prolonged fasting or insufficient glucose availability.\r\n\r\nIn the absence of insulin, glucose uptake and utilization in insulin-dependent tissues (such as skeletal muscle and adipose tissue) are impaired, leading to increased fatty acid breakdown and ketone body formation in the liver.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 978,979.","responses":[{"text":"Amino acid uptake","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ketogenesis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Shift of potassium from Extracellular fluid to cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose uptake and utilization","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12914,"text":"The nervous pathway involving the passage of light signals from the eyes to activate or deactivate the pineal gland passes from which of the following hypothalamic nuclei?","explanation":"The **pineal gland** is an endocrine gland located in the brain that plays a crucial role in the regulation of **circadian rhythms**, including the sleep-wake cycle. The gland secretes the hormone **melatonin**, which is involved in signaling the body about day and night cycles.\r\n\r\nThe nervous pathway involved in the passage of light signals from the eyes to activate or deactivate the pineal gland is mediated by the **suprachiasmatic nuclei** (SCN). The SCN are located in the **hypothalamus** and are considered the master circadian pacemaker of the body.\r\n\r\nLight signals detected by the **retina** of the eyes are transmitted through the **retinohypothalamic tract** to the SCN. The SCN then synchronizes the production and secretion of melatonin from the pineal gland, regulating the sleep-wake cycle and other circadian rhythms.","reference":"Arendt J, Aulinas A. Physiology of the pineal gland and melatonin. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Boyce A, et al., eds. Endotext. MDText.com, Inc.; 2000. Accessed December 5, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK550972/","responses":[{"text":"Subthalamic nuclei","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior hypothalamus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arcuate nuclei","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Supraoptic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suprachiasmatic","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12915,"text":"Receptors for peptide hormones are located on the surface of cell membranes due to which of the following properties of these hormones?","explanation":"Peptide hormones, such as insulin, glucagon, and growth hormone, are large molecules composed of amino acids. They possess a **hydrophilic** (water-loving) nature, as they have many charged and polar groups on their surface. Due to this hydrophilic nature, these hormones are unable to cross the hydrophobic lipid bilayer of the cell membrane.\r\n\r\nTo exert their effects, peptide hormones interact with their target cells through specific **cell surface receptors**. These receptors are integral proteins located on the **plasma membrane** of target cells. When a peptide hormone binds to its receptor, it initiates a series of intracellular signaling cascades, leading to the generation of **second messenger molecules**, such as cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) or inositol triphosphate (IP3).\r\n\r\nThese second messengers, in turn, activate various **effector systems** inside the cell, mediating the cellular response to the hormone signal.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, **lipophilic** (lipid-loving) hormones, such as steroid hormones and thyroid hormones, are able to cross the cell membrane due to their hydrophobic nature. These hormones bind to intracellular receptors located in the cytoplasm or nucleus and directly influence gene expression.","reference":"Karlson P. [Hormone receptors and hormone action (Author’s transl)]. Klinische Wochenschrift. Published June 15, 1979. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/224243/","responses":[{"text":"Effector system","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrophobic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lipophilic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrophilic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"High affinity for cAMP","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13214,"text":"Which of the following hormones inhibits the production of cholecystokinin?","explanation":"**Cholecystokinin (CCK)** is a peptide hormone produced by cells in the **duodenum** and **jejunum** of the small intestine. Its primary role is to regulate digestive processes, particularly the stimulation of pancreatic enzyme secretion and gallbladder contraction in response to the presence of fats and proteins in the small intestine.\r\n\r\n**Somatostatin** is another peptide hormone that is produced by **delta cells** in the **pancreatic islets** and the **duodenum**. It has inhibitory effects on various digestive functions, including the suppression of hormone release.\r\n\r\nSomatostatin acts as an **inhibitor of cholecystokinin** production. When somatostatin is released in response to the presence of chyme (partially digested food) in the small intestine, it decreases the release of cholecystokinin. As a result, the secretion of pancreatic enzymes and gallbladder contraction, which are stimulated by CCK, are reduced, allowing for more controlled digestion and nutrient absorption.","reference":"Herzig KH, Louie DS, Owyang C. Somatostatin inhibits CCK release by inhibiting secretion and action of CCK-releasing peptide. The American Journal of Physiology. Published June 1994. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/7517637/","responses":[{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Growth hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucagon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenaline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatostatin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13215,"text":"Which of the following metal ions is required for the storage and crystallization of insulin?","explanation":"**Zinc ion** is required for the proper storage and crystallization of insulin. Inside the beta cells of the pancreas, insulin molecules associate with zinc ions to form hexamers, which are the stable storage form of insulin. The interaction between insulin and zinc facilitates the formation of these hexamers, allowing the hormone to be stored in dense crystalline granules within the beta cells.\r\n\r\nWhen blood glucose levels rise, insulin is secreted by exocytosis of these granules, and the zinc-insulin interaction is essential for proper insulin secretion.","reference":"Maret W. Zinc in pancreatic islet biology, insulin sensitivity, and diabetes. Preventive Nutrition and Food Science. Published March 2017. Accessed December 9, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5383135/","responses":[{"text":"Manganate ion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnesium ion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Potassium ion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium ion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zinc ion","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13216,"text":"Which of the following metabolic enzymes is inhibited by insulin?","explanation":"**Insulin** is a hormone secreted by the pancreas in response to elevated blood glucose levels, and it plays a critical role in regulating various metabolic processes in the body. One of the important actions of insulin is to promote **anabolic** (energy storage) processes and **inhibit catabolic** (energy breakdown) processes.\r\n\r\n**Hormone sensitive lipase** is an enzyme involved in the breakdown of triglycerides into free fatty acids and glycerol. It is primarily active in adipose tissue and plays a key role in releasing stored fatty acids when energy demands are high, such as during fasting or physical activity.\r\n\r\n**Insulin inhibits hormone-sensitive lipase** as part of its anabolic effects. When insulin is present in the bloodstream, it suppresses the release of free fatty acids from adipose tissue, promoting fat storage and preventing excessive fat breakdown.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 977.","responses":[{"text":"Glucokinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycogen synthetase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphofructokinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hormone sensitive lipase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetyl Co-A carboxylase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13224,"text":"After undergoing total thyroidectomy for follicular carcinoma of the thyroid a 50-year-old man develops a tingling sensation and neuromuscular instability post-operatively. Which of the following laboratory test should be carried out on an urgent basis to determine the further proceedings of the therapy?","explanation":"After undergoing total thyroidectomy for follicular carcinoma of the thyroid, the 50-year-old man develops tingling sensations and neuromuscular instability post-operatively. These symptoms are highly suggestive of **hypocalcemia**, which is a common complication after thyroid surgery due to inadvertent damage or removal of the parathyroid glands.\r\n\r\nThe **parathyroid glands** are responsible for producing **parathyroid hormone (PTH)**, which plays a crucial role in maintaining calcium levels in the blood. If the parathyroid glands are damaged or removed during thyroid surgery, it can lead to a deficiency of PTH and subsequent hypocalcemia.\r\n\r\nTo determine the further proceedings of therapy and to address the potential hypocalcemia, an urgent laboratory test for **serum parathormone (PTH)** levels should be carried out. Low or undetectable PTH levels would confirm post-thyroidectomy hypoparathyroidism, and prompt intervention is necessary to correct the calcium imbalance.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 1104.","responses":[{"text":"Thyroid stimulating hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serotonin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum calcium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iodine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parathormone","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13232,"text":"A 49-year-old female experienced multiple attacks of abdominal pain last year. Three times she had passed stones in the urine during these episodes of pain. Now she is experiencing pain in her right middle finger for one month. On physical examination, her finger is tender. Laboratory reports show calcium 13.7 mg/ dL, phosphate 1.9 mg/ dL, and Creatinine 1.1mg/ dL, albumin 4.8 mg/ dL. Which of the following bone lesions is she most likely to have?","explanation":"**Osteitis Fibrosa Cystica** is a bone disorder commonly associated with **primary hyperparathyroidism**. In this condition, there is excessive secretion of parathyroid hormone (PTH) by the parathyroid glands, leading to increased bone resorption, elevated serum calcium levels (hypercalcemia), and decreased serum phosphate levels (hypophosphatemia).\r\n\r\nThe increased bone resorption causes the formation of **cysts** within the bones and fibrous tissue replacement, leading to weakened and tender bones. This can result in bone pain and deformities. The elevated serum calcium levels can lead to the formation of urinary stones (nephrolithiasis).\r\n\r\nThe laboratory findings of elevated calcium and phosphate levels, along with the clinical presentation of bone pain and previous episodes of urinary stones, support the diagnosis of **Osteitis Fibrosa Cystica** in this patient.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 1103.","responses":[{"text":"Osteoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteochondroma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteitis fibrosa cystica","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteomyelitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13239,"text":"A 57-year-old man is found comatose. On physical examination, he has decreased skin turgor. Laboratory studies show a blood glucose of 780 mg/ dL. Urinalysis reveals ketosis and proteinuria along with 4+ glycosuria. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The clinical presentation of a 57-year-old man with comatose status, decreased skin turgor, hyperglycemia (blood glucose of 780 mg/dL), ketosis, proteinuria, and 4+ glycosuria is highly indicative of **Type-I diabetes mellitus**.\r\n\r\n**Type-I diabetes mellitus** is an autoimmune disorder characterized by the destruction of pancreatic beta cells, leading to an absolute deficiency of insulin. Without insulin, glucose cannot enter cells for energy utilization, resulting in hyperglycemia. The absence of insulin also causes the body to break down fats for energy, leading to the production of ketones and ketosis.\r\n\r\nThe high blood glucose levels exceed the renal threshold, causing glycosuria (glucose in urine), leading to an osmotic diuresis that leads to dehydration and decreased skin turgor. The proteinuria can be a consequence of chronic hyperglycemia and kidney damage.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 1110","responses":[{"text":"Cushing syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type-II diabetes mellitus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type-I diabetes mellitus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Neuroendocrine tumor secreting glucagon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ingestion of large quantity of sugar","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13321,"text":"A clinical study is performed involving subjects who developed Addison's disease. They were recorded to have laboratory studies with hyponatremia, hyperkalemia, hypoglycemia, and decreased plasma cortisol. They became hypotensive. In some subjects, this disease had an acute onset in less than 2 days. Which of the following conditions is most likely to produce this acute course?","explanation":"The clinical presentation of Addison's disease in the context of hyponatremia, hyperkalemia, hypoglycemia, decreased plasma cortisol, and hypotension, with an acute onset in less than 2 days, is highly suggestive of Waterhouse-Friedrichsen syndrome.\r\n\r\n**Waterhouse-Friedrichsen syndrome** is a rare but severe condition characterized by acute adrenal insufficiency due to bilateral adrenal gland hemorrhage. It is usually caused by **severe bacterial infection**, most commonly by **Neisseria meningitidis** (meningococcal septicemia). The bacteria release toxins that damage blood vessel walls, leading to bleeding into the adrenal glands and subsequent adrenal crisis.\r\n\r\nThe clinical manifestations of Waterhouse-Friedrichsen syndrome are sudden and rapidly progressive, with patients experiencing shock and multi-organ dysfunction. The adrenal hemorrhage results in an acute decrease in cortisol production, leading to the symptoms of adrenal insufficiency.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 1129.","responses":[{"text":"Reactive systemic amyloidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Disseminated Mycobacterium tuberculosis infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Waterhouse-Friedrichsen syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Metastatic small cell anaplastic carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blunt force abdominal trauma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13322,"text":"A 35-year-old young male working in a marketing company was referred to you by a cardiologist after a minor angina attack. He complained of decreased sleep and pain in neck muscles. He works almost 10 to 12 hours a day and rides motorbikes to meet his clients in the city. He gained weight of 15 Kg in the last two months, having a body mass index of 35 Kg/m^2. What could be the possible reason for his recent attack?","explanation":"The possible reason for the 35-year-old male's recent angina attack is the **nature of his job** in the marketing company.\r\n\r\n1. **Stress and Long Working Hours:** His occupation in marketing is known for its high-stress environment with long working hours (10 to 12 hours a day). Chronic stress can lead to the release of stress hormones like adrenaline and cortisol, which can adversely affect the cardiovascular system, increasing the risk of angina.\r\n\r\n2. **Motorbike Rides:** Riding motorbikes to meet clients in the city can expose him to traffic-related stress and air pollution, both of which have been associated with an increased risk of cardiovascular events.\r\n\r\n3. **Weight Gain and Obesity:** The significant weight gain (15 kg) and high body mass index (BMI of 35 kg/m^2) are also likely related to his sedentary work lifestyle and long hours, contributing to the development of obesity, a significant risk factor for angina and heart disease.\r\n\r\n4. **Sleep Disturbances:** His complaints of decreased sleep may be linked to the stress and long working hours, which can adversely affect sleep patterns and contribute to cardiovascular risk.","reference":"Angina - Symptoms and causes. Mayo Clinic. Accessed December 10, 2022. https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/angina/symptoms-causes/syc-203693","responses":[{"text":"Stress induced increase in IL-6 and CRP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Riding a motorbike","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nature of job","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Age factor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased sleep","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13323,"text":"Erikson postulated that every stage is basically a defined period of age in which a particular conflict arises. The way these conflicts are dealt with will determine the end result which can be either a successful resolution or a continuation of the conflict. If the conflict is resolved, the stage is satisfied, an inner attribute will be acquired. What is this inner attribute?","explanation":"Erik Erikson, a renowned developmental psychologist, proposed a theory of psychosocial development consisting of eight stages, each corresponding to a particular age range and a unique psychosocial conflict. The successful resolution of these conflicts leads to the acquisition of specific virtues.\r\n\r\nIn Erikson's theory, the **inner attribute** that is acquired when a stage is successfully resolved is called a **virtue**. A virtue is a positive psychological quality or strength developed as a result of successfully navigating and resolving the psychosocial conflict at each stage.\r\n\r\nFor example, in the first stage of Erikson's theory, which occurs during infancy (0-1 year), the conflict is **Trust vs. Mistrust**. If an infant experiences consistent care and nurturing from their caregivers, they develop a sense of trust and a feeling of basic trustworthiness in the world. The virtue acquired from successfully resolving this conflict is **Hope**.\r\n\r\nThroughout the subsequent stages of Erikson's theory, successful resolutions lead to the acquisition of different virtues, each contributing to the individual's overall personality development.","reference":"Orenstein GA, Lewis L. Eriksons stages of psychosocial development. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed December 10, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK556096/","responses":[{"text":"Self esteem","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Self concept","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Self identity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Virtue","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Self worth","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13324,"text":"Which of the following endocrine glands is heavily dependent on the trace mineral iodine?","explanation":"The endocrine gland that is heavily dependent on the trace mineral **iodine** is the **thyroid gland**.\r\n\r\nThe thyroid gland is a butterfly-shaped gland located in the front of the neck and plays a crucial role in the synthesis and secretion of thyroid hormones (thyroxine - T4 and triiodothyronine - T3). These hormones are essential for regulating various physiological processes, including metabolism, growth, and development.\r\n\r\nIodine is an essential component of both T4 and T3, as it forms an integral part of their molecular structure. The thyroid gland actively takes up iodine from the bloodstream to synthesize these hormones. Iodine deficiency can lead to decreased production of T4 and T3, resulting in a condition called **hypothyroidism**, which is associated with a range of symptoms, including fatigue, weight gain, and mental sluggishness.","reference":"Ahad F, Ganie SA. Iodine, Iodine metabolism and Iodine deficiency disorders revisited. Indian J Endocrinol Metab. 2010;14(1):13-17. Accessed December 10, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3063534/","responses":[{"text":"Thymus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pineal gland","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid gland","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13325,"text":"A 50-year-old male known case of diabetes was advised by the physician to reduce his waist circumference. Which of the following options contains a maximum cut-off for males after which the risk of comorbidity increases?","explanation":"The maximum waist circumference cut-off for males after which the risk of comorbidity increases is **greater than 102 cm (40 inches)**. Exceeding this cut-off indicates a higher level of visceral fat deposition, which is associated with adverse health outcomes.\r\n\r\nIndividuals with a waist circumference greater than this value are considered to have central obesity and are at an elevated risk of developing diabetes-related complications and other health issues. Therefore, reducing waist circumference is essential for improving health outcomes, particularly in individuals with diabetes.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Endocrinology Module, Community medicine, Topic: obesity, slide 22.","responses":[{"text":"Greater than 130 cm (51 inches)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Greater than 100 cm (39 inches)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Greater than 102 cm (40 inches)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Greater than 90 cm (35 inches)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Greater than 88 cm(34.6 inches)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13327,"text":"A 30-year-old female patient, obese, nondiabetic, presented with significant weight gain, easy fatiguability, and lethargy. On examination, she looked pale, obese, and slightly confused. Her blood pressure is 170/90 mmHg, and her pulse rate is 52 beats/min. She was unable to stand from a sitting position without support and her deep tendon reflexes were diminished. With the given scenario, what is the probable diagnosis?","explanation":"**Hypothyroidism** is a condition characterized by an insufficient production of thyroid hormones (thyroxine - T4 and triiodothyronine - T3) by the thyroid gland. The deficiency of these hormones leads to a decreased metabolic rate and a range of clinical manifestations:\r\n\r\n1. **Weight Gain and Easy Fatiguability:** Reduced metabolic rate in hypothyroidism can result in weight gain and fatigue.\r\n\r\n2. **Lethargy and Confusion:** Patients with hypothyroidism may experience decreased mental alertness, lethargy, and cognitive impairment.\r\n\r\n3. **Pale Appearance:** Hypothyroidism can lead to a pale and puffy facial appearance.\r\n\r\n4. **Hypertension with Bradycardia:** Elevated blood pressure (as seen in the scenario - 170/90 mmHg) and bradycardia (52 beats/min) can occur due to changes in cardiac function.\r\n\r\n5. **Muscle Weakness and Diminished Reflexes:** Hypothyroidism can lead to muscle weakness, making it difficult for the patient to stand from a sitting position without support, and may cause diminished deep tendon reflexes.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 1125.","responses":[{"text":"Cushing syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstructive sleep apnea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothyroidism","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Polycystic ovarian disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obesity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14650,"text":"A 55-year-old female presents to her primary care physician with uncontrolled hypertension. She reports no symptoms but her blood pressure is found to be consistently elevated in her recent visits. She has been on multiple anti-hypertensive medications without success. Laboratory tests reveal low plasma renin activity and high aldosterone levels. What is the next best investigation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's medicine, 24th edition, page 674","responses":[{"text":"Renal biopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma metanephrines","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Doppler ultrasound of abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brain MRI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CT scan abdomen","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15141,"text":"A 45-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a 2-week history of fatigue, weakness, and weight loss. He also complains of nausea, vomiting, and dizziness. He has a history of chronic corticosteroid use for rheumatoid arthritis. On examination, he is hypotensive and has hyperpigmentation of the skin. His laboratory results show low sodium, glucose, and high potassium levels. Serum cortisol is low. What is the next best step in management?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Morning ACTH levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dexamethasone suppression test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Saline challenge test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intravenous normal saline and hydrocortisone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Abdominal CT scan","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15499,"text":"Which of the following nerve is damaged during thyroidectomy?","explanation":"During a thyroidectomy, which is the surgical removal of part or all of the thyroid gland, one of the critical structures at risk of damage is the **recurrent laryngeal nerve** (RLN).\r\n\r\nThe RLN is a branch of the vagus nerve (cranial nerve X) that innervates the muscles controlling the vocal cords in the larynx (voice box). It has a complex and extensive course, winding around the thyroid gland on both sides. On the right side, the RLN loops around the subclavian artery, and on the left side, it loops around the aortic arch.\r\n\r\nDuring a thyroidectomy, surgeons must be cautious not to damage or inadvertently cut the RLN. Injury to the RLN can lead to vocal cord paralysis or paresis, which may cause voice changes, hoarseness, and difficulty in speaking. In severe cases, bilateral RLN injury can result in airway compromise and respiratory distress.","reference":"Liu N, Chen B, Li L, et al. Recurrent laryngeal nerve injury near the nerve entry point in total endoscopic thyroidectomy: a retrospective cohort study. Cancer Management and Research. Published December 1, 2021. Accessed July 25, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8645946/","responses":[{"text":"Recurrent laryngeal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior laryngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior thyroid artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior thyroid artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior laryngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15500,"text":"What is the length of the parathyroid gland?","explanation":"The length of the parathyroid gland is typically around **6 mm**. These glands are relatively small structures, and their size can vary slightly among individuals.\r\n\r\nThe parathyroid glands are usually present in pairs, with four glands being the most common arrangement. However, the number of parathyroid glands can vary, and some individuals may have additional glands or fewer than four.\r\n\r\nDue to their small size and location, the parathyroid glands are challenging to visualize and assess directly without medical imaging techniques.","reference":"Sung JY. Parathyroid ultrasonography: the evolving role of the radiologist. Ultrasonography. Published October 2015. Accessed July 25, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4603207/","responses":[{"text":"26 mm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"6 mm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"15 cm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"6 cm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"26 cm","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15656,"text":"Which of the following substances is not a known stimulator for glucagon release?","explanation":"Among the substances listed, **gamma-butyric acid (GABA)** is **not** a known stimulator for glucagon release. GABA is an inhibitory neurotransmitter in the central nervous system and functions to reduce neuronal activity, primarily promoting inhibitory effects.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, the following substances are known to stimulate glucagon release:\r\n\r\n1. **Theophylline:** A bronchodilator used to treat respiratory conditions, and it can stimulate glucagon release, leading to increased blood glucose levels.\r\n\r\n2. **Growth Hormone:** A hormone produced by the pituitary gland, it can stimulate glucagon release, promoting an increase in blood glucose levels.\r\n\r\n3. **Cholecystokinin (CCK):** A hormone produced in the gastrointestinal tract, it can stimulate glucagon release to regulate nutrient metabolism.\r\n\r\n4. **Cortisol:** A hormone produced by the adrenal cortex, it can stimulate glucagon release, contributing to increased blood glucose levels during stress.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 792, 962, 984.","responses":[{"text":"Growth hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cortisol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholecystokinin (CCK)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gamma-butyric acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Theophylline","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15657,"text":"What is the name of the sweet odor breath that is often associated with uncontrolled diabetes?","explanation":"The sweet odor breath that is often associated with uncontrolled diabetes is known as **acetone breath**. This distinctive fruity or sweet smell on the breath is a characteristic feature of a serious complication in diabetes called **diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA)**.\r\n\r\nDKA occurs when there is a severe insulin deficiency in the body, leading to the breakdown of fats as an alternative source of energy. As fats are broken down, they produce **ketones**, including acetone, which are acidic byproducts. The accumulation of ketones in the blood leads to a state of **ketoacidosis**, characterized by a drop in blood pH.\r\n\r\nOne of the ketones, acetone, is volatile and can be exhaled through the lungs, resulting in the sweet odor breath. The acetone breath is a critical clinical clue for diagnosing DKA and is often accompanied by other symptoms such as excessive thirst, frequent urination, nausea, vomiting, and abdominal pain.","reference":"Sha MS, Maurya MR, Shafath S, et al. Breath analysis for the in vivo detection of diabetic ketoacidosis. ACS Omega. Published February 8, 2022. Accessed July 25, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8830064/","responses":[{"text":"Methane breath","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Halitosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetone breath","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Garlic breath","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ammonia breath","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15658,"text":"A 50-year-old lady presents to the emergency department with an enlarged thyroid, protruded eyes, severe palpitations, sweating, and complaints of fatigue. What is the diagnosis?","explanation":"**Graves' disease** is an autoimmune disorder in which the body's immune system produces antibodies that stimulate the thyroid gland to produce excessive amounts of thyroid hormones (thyroxine - T4 and triiodothyronine - T3). This overproduction of thyroid hormones leads to a state of hyperthyroidism, characterized by an increased metabolic rate and various clinical features:\r\n\r\n1. **Enlarged Thyroid (Goiter):** The thyroid gland becomes enlarged due to the stimulation of thyroid hormone production.\r\n\r\n2. **Protruded Eyes (Exophthalmos):** Graves' disease can cause inflammation and swelling of the tissues around the eyes, leading to exophthalmos, where the eyes appear to protrude from their sockets.\r\n\r\n3. **Severe Palpitations, Sweating, and Fatigue:** These symptoms are common manifestations of hyperthyroidism, reflecting the increased sympathetic nervous system activity and heightened metabolic state.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1082.","responses":[{"text":"Hashimoto's thyroiditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Multinodular goiter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Graves disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Myxedema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endemic goiter","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15659,"text":"A man is very self-conscious about hygiene so he is always washing his hands and wearing gloves. Which psychosexual stage of development did he potentially skip?","explanation":"According to Sigmund Freud's psychosexual theory of development, children pass through various stages, each focusing on specific erogenous zones and associated conflicts. The stages include the **oral, anal, phallic, latency, and genital stages**.\r\n\r\nIn the scenario described, the man's excessive preoccupation with hygiene, constant hand washing, and wearing gloves suggest potential fixation or skipping of the **anal stage** of psychosexual development.\r\n\r\nThe anal stage typically occurs between 18 months and 3 years of age, during which the child's primary focus is on the sensations associated with bowel movements and the process of toilet training. Successful completion of toilet training fosters a sense of autonomy and self-control, while parental overcontrol or harshness during this stage may lead to conflicts and fixations.\r\n\r\nThe man's self-consciousness about hygiene, specifically his preoccupation with cleanliness and handwashing, may indicate unresolved conflicts related to the anal stage. These conflicts could potentially manifest as traits of excessive orderliness, meticulousness, and a need for control later in life.","reference":"Freud’s psychosexual development in psychology 101 at allpsych online | allpsych. Published August 21, 2014. Accessed August 1, 2023. https://allpsych.com/psychology101/personality/sexual_development/","responses":[{"text":"Genital stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phallic stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Latency stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anal stage","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15660,"text":"A 5-year-old boy is frequently biting himself and putting objects in his mouth. Which psychosexual stage of development may he be experiencing?","explanation":"According to Sigmund Freud's psychosexual theory of development, children progress through different stages, each with a focus on specific erogenous zones and associated conflicts. The stages include the **oral, anal, phallic, latency, and genital stages**.\r\n\r\nIn the scenario described, the 5-year-old boy's behavior of frequently biting himself and putting objects in his mouth suggests that he may be experiencing the **oral stage** of psychosexual development.\r\n\r\nDuring the oral stage, which occurs from birth to around 18 months of age, the primary erogenous zone is the mouth. Children at this stage explore the world primarily through their mouths, as it is a source of pleasure and comfort. Biting and putting objects in the mouth are common behaviors during this stage, as they serve as a way for the child to satisfy their oral needs and seek pleasure.\r\n\r\nFreud proposed that unresolved conflicts during each stage could lead to fixations and potential personality traits later in life. In the oral stage, unresolved conflicts may manifest as oral fixations, such as excessive dependency or a tendency to overeat or smoke.","reference":"Freud’s psychosexual development in psychology 101 at allpsych online | allpsych. Published August 21, 2014. Accessed August 1, 2023. https://allpsych.com/psychology101/personality/sexual_development/","responses":[{"text":"Anal stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral stage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Latency stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Genital stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phallic stage","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15944,"text":"A 50-year-old diabetic man presents to the outpatient department. The medication prescribed to him will lower his Hb1Ac down to which value?","explanation":"HbA1c (Glycated Hemoglobin) is a crucial marker used to assess long-term glycemic control in individuals with diabetes. It reflects the average blood glucose levels over the past 2 to 3 months.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the medication prescribed to the 50-year-old diabetic man is expected to lower his HbA1c down to **6.5%**. This target value is widely accepted in clinical practice and is recommended by various diabetes management guidelines. Achieving an HbA1c level of 6.5% or below indicates good glycemic control, reducing the risk of diabetes-related complications, such as cardiovascular disease, nephropathy, and retinopathy.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1098, 1099.","responses":[{"text":"\u003e 7%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"\u003e 6.5%","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"\u003e 6%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"\u003e 10%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"\u003e 5%","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15988,"text":"Which of the following may present in a female with hypothyroidism?","explanation":"Hypothyroidism is a condition characterized by insufficient production of thyroid hormones (thyroxine - T4 and triiodothyronine - T3) by the thyroid gland. It leads to a decreased metabolic rate and affects various physiological processes.\r\n\r\n**Somnolence**, which refers to increased drowsiness and a tendency to fall asleep easily, is a common manifestation in females with hypothyroidism. The decreased metabolic rate caused by the deficiency of thyroid hormones leads to reduced energy levels, lethargy, and a feeling of constant fatigue. As a result, individuals with hypothyroidism may experience daytime sleepiness and find it difficult to stay alert and awake.\r\n\r\nWhile other options, such as **goiter**, **heat intolerance**, **weight loss**, and **tachycardia**, may be characteristic of other thyroid disorders like hyperthyroidism, they are not typical features of hypothyroidism.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1078.","responses":[{"text":"Somnolence","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Weight loss","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Goiter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tachycardia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heat intolerance","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15989,"text":"Which of the following is the most potent corticosteroid?","explanation":"Among the options provided, **Dexamethasone** is the most potent corticosteroid. It exhibits a high binding affinity for glucocorticoid receptors and has a more extended duration of action compared to other corticosteroids.\r\n\r\n**Prednisone** and **Cortisone** are intermediate-acting corticosteroids, and they require metabolic conversion in the liver to become biologically active.\r\n\r\n**Cortisol** (hydrocortisone) is the endogenous glucocorticoid and has a relatively potent anti-inflammatory effect but has a shorter duration of action compared to dexamethasone.\r\n\r\n**Corticosterone** is a weaker glucocorticoid and is mainly involved in regulating salt and water balance rather than exerting potent anti-inflammatory effects.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 756.","responses":[{"text":"Cortisol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prednisone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corticosterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dexamethasone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cortisone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15990,"text":"Which of the following counteracts the negative effects of cortisol?","explanation":"Cortisol, a glucocorticoid hormone produced by the adrenal cortex, plays a vital role in the body's response to stress and regulation of various physiological processes. While cortisol is essential for maintaining homeostasis during stress, excessive or prolonged elevation of cortisol levels can have negative effects on the body.\r\n\r\nThe **sleep-wake cycle**, also known as the circadian rhythm, is crucial for the regulation of cortisol secretion. Cortisol follows a diurnal pattern, with its highest levels typically occurring in the early morning upon waking and gradually declining throughout the day, reaching its lowest point at night during sleep.\r\n\r\nA well-regulated sleep-wake cycle helps counteract the negative effects of cortisol by promoting its appropriate secretion and timing. Adequate and quality sleep supports a healthy cortisol rhythm, ensuring that cortisol levels are highest when needed for morning activities and gradually decrease during the day and night.\r\n\r\nDisruptions in the sleep-wake cycle, such as irregular sleep patterns, jet lag, or chronic sleep deprivation, can lead to dysregulation of cortisol secretion, which may contribute to adverse effects like impaired immune function, metabolic disturbances, and mood alterations.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 964, 967.","responses":[{"text":"Stress","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperglycemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sleep-wake cycle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"CRH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ACTH","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15991,"text":"How does cortisol exert its anti-inflammatory effects?","explanation":"When inflammation occurs, immune cells release pro-inflammatory substances like cytokines and chemokines, leading to increased vascular permeability and the migration of immune cells to the site of inflammation. Cortisol, a glucocorticoid hormone, modulates this process by reducing the production of pro-inflammatory cytokines and inhibiting the activity of immune cells involved in inflammation.\r\n\r\nOne of the key anti-inflammatory actions of cortisol is to **stabilize lysosomal membranes**. Lysosomes contain enzymes that, when released, can cause tissue damage and exacerbate inflammation. By stabilizing lysosomal membranes, cortisol prevents the uncontrolled release of these enzymes and reduces tissue damage.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, cortisol **decreases capillary permeability**, preventing fluid and immune cells from leaking into tissues, which further contributes to the reduction of inflammation.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 965.","responses":[{"text":"By increasing the phagocytosis of the damaged cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By increasing the release of IL-1 from WBCs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By increasing lymphocyte production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By stabilizing lysosomal membranes and decreasing permeability of the capillaries","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"All of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15992,"text":"Which hormone functions as the second line of defence to prevent hypoglycemia?","explanation":"**Glucagon** is the hormone that acts as the second line of defense against hypoglycemia after decrease in insulin levels. It is secreted by the alpha cells of the pancreas when blood glucose levels fall, and it promotes the breakdown of glycogen to glucose in the liver (glycogenolysis) and the formation of glucose from non-carbohydrate sources (gluconeogenesis).\r\n\r\nEpinephrine is the second-line defense in counterregulatory response to hypoglycemia. Insulin, on the other hand, is a hormone that lowers blood glucose levels and decrease in insulin levels is often the first line of defense in hypoglycemia.","reference":"(1) Cryer PE. The barrier of hypoglycemia in diabetes. Diabetes. Published December 1, 2008. Accessed January 5, 2024. https://diabetesjournals.org/diabetes/article/57/12/3169/12810/The-Barrier-of-Hypoglycemia-in-Diabetes\r\n\r\n(2) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 981, 983.","responses":[{"text":"Cortisol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Growth hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucagon","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Epinephrine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15993,"text":"If a person is given steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs, what will be the drug's effect on this person?","explanation":"When a person is given steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs, such as synthetic glucocorticoids, the drugs mimic the action of cortisol, a natural glucocorticoid hormone produced by the adrenal cortex. These drugs have potent anti-inflammatory and immunosuppressive properties, making them effective in treating various inflammatory conditions.\r\n\r\nThe administration of exogenous glucocorticoids leads to an increase in blood cortisol levels. As a result, the hypothalamus detects this elevated cortisol concentration and reduces the release of **corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH)**. CRH is the hormone responsible for stimulating the release of adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) from the anterior pituitary.\r\n\r\nWith decreased CRH secretion, the release of **ACTH** is consequently reduced. Since ACTH is the primary stimulator of cortisol synthesis and secretion from the adrenal cortex, its lower levels lead to a decrease in cortisol production despite the presence of exogenous glucocorticoids.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 967.","responses":[{"text":"High cortisol, high CRH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High cortisol, low ACTH","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Low cortisol, high ACTH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High CRH, high ACTH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low ACTH, low CRH","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16039,"text":"Which of the following tests will be used to measure the average blood glucose levels of a 30-year-old man over the past 3 months?","explanation":"To assess the average blood glucose levels of a 30-year-old man over the past 3 months, the **HbA1c** (Glycated Hemoglobin) test is the most appropriate choice.\r\n\r\nHbA1c reflects the amount of glucose that has become bound to hemoglobin in red blood cells over their lifespan, which is approximately 120 days. As red blood cells circulate throughout the body, they continuously accumulate glucose in proportion to the prevailing blood glucose levels. Therefore, HbA1c provides a reliable estimate of the average blood glucose concentration over the past 2 to 3 months.\r\n\r\nUnlike other tests, such as **glucose tolerance test** or **fasting blood sugar test**, which provide a snapshot of glucose levels at specific moments, HbA1c offers a long-term perspective, making it ideal for monitoring chronic glycemic control in conditions like diabetes.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 987-988.","responses":[{"text":"Random blood glucose test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbA1c","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fasting blood sugar test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose tolerance test","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16040,"text":"The energy for transporting iodide across the Na-I symporter comes from which of the following?","explanation":"The uptake of iodide (I-) from the bloodstream into thyroid follicular cells is a crucial step in thyroid hormone synthesis. This process is mediated by a **sodium-iodide symporter (Na-I symporter)**, which actively transports iodide ions into the cell against their concentration gradient, using the energy derived from the activity of **Na-K ATPase**.\r\n\r\nThe Na-K ATPase is a transmembrane enzyme found on the basolateral membrane of thyroid follicular cells. It actively pumps **sodium ions (Na+)** out of the cell and **potassium ions (K+)** into the cell. This action maintains a low intracellular sodium concentration and a high intracellular potassium concentration.\r\n\r\nThe energy derived from the hydrolysis of ATP by Na-K ATPase creates a sodium gradient, with higher extracellular sodium levels and lower intracellular sodium levels. This gradient provides the driving force for the Na-I symporter to transport iodide into the cell by coupling the movement of iodide to the inward movement of sodium ions.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 941-942.","responses":[{"text":"Na-K-Cl pump","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Na-K ATPase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"H-K ATPase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"SGLT-2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT-3","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16043,"text":"Which of these is mainly responsible for the exocytosis of thyroid hormone?","explanation":"The key player in the exocytosis of thyroid hormone is the **lysosomes** within thyroid follicular cells. Lysosomes are membrane-bound organelles containing various enzymes responsible for the degradation of substances within the cell.\r\n\r\nDuring thyroid hormone secretion, lysosomes fuse with the apical membrane of the thyroid follicular cells, where thyroglobulin-containing vesicles also fuse. The lysosomal enzymes then digest thyroglobulin, liberating free thyroid hormones (T4 and T3) into the follicular cell cytoplasm. Subsequently, these thyroid hormones diffuse across the basolateral membrane of the cell and enter the bloodstream, where they exert their physiological effects on target tissues.\r\n\r\nWhile the other options, such as the Na-K symporter, peroxidase, pendrin, and thyronine, are involved in various aspects of thyroid hormone synthesis and transport, they are not directly responsible for the exocytosis of thyroid hormone as lysosomes are.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 943.","responses":[{"text":"Lysosomes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Peroxidase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Na-K symporter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyronine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pendrin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16044,"text":"Which of the following gives rise to thyroid follicular cells?","explanation":"During embryonic development, the thyroid gland originates from the endodermal tissue. The thyroid gland arises as an endodermal diverticulum known as the **thyroid diverticulum** or **thyroid primordium**. This diverticulum emerges as an outpouching from the floor of the pharynx, specifically from the **median endodermal tissue** at the level of the **foramen cecum**, which is located between the first and second pharyngeal arches.\r\n\r\nAs the thyroid diverticulum descends, it migrates anteriorly to the developing pharynx. During this process, the diverticulum gives rise to two major cell types within the thyroid gland: the **thyroid follicular cells** and the **parafollicular cells** (C cells).\r\n\r\n**Thyroid follicular cells**, responsible for producing and secreting thyroid hormones (thyroxine - T4 and triiodothyronine - T3), arise from the **endodermal** component of the thyroid diverticulum. These cells will later form the spherical structures known as thyroid follicles, where the synthesis and storage of thyroid hormones occur.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, the **parafollicular cells (C cells)** develop from the neural crest-derived cells within the **4th and 5th pharyngeal pouches**. These cells produce calcitonin, a hormone that regulates calcium metabolism.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th edition. Elsevier; 2016: 168.","responses":[{"text":"3rd pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoderm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesenchyme","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2nd pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16048,"text":"Which type of vessels are present between cords of the pancreas?","explanation":"The pancreas is a vital organ involved in both endocrine and exocrine functions. Within the exocrine portion, the pancreas contains clusters of cells known as **acini**, arranged in cords. The acini are responsible for producing digestive enzymes that are secreted into the pancreatic ducts.\r\n\r\nThe vascular supply to the pancreas is critical for maintaining its functions. Between the cords of the pancreas, the **capillaries** play a significant role in facilitating nutrient exchange and waste removal. Specifically, the **fenestrated capillaries** are the type of vessels present in this location.\r\n\r\nFenestrated capillaries are characterized by the presence of **fenestrations**, which are small pores or openings in their endothelial cells. These fenestrations enhance the permeability of the capillaries, allowing for efficient exchange of nutrients, hormones, and waste products between the blood and the pancreatic cells.\r\n\r\nThe presence of fenestrated capillaries is crucial for providing the necessary nutrients to the pancreatic acinar cells and ensuring the efficient removal of waste products generated during enzyme production. This vascular arrangement supports the exocrine functions of the pancreas, allowing it to fulfill its role in digestion.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 418.","responses":[{"text":"Fenestrated capillaries","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Continuous capillaries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sinusoid capillaries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elastic arteries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Venules","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16052,"text":"Which of these is a major cause of metabolic syndromes?","explanation":"Metabolic syndrome is a cluster of interconnected metabolic abnormalities that significantly increase the risk of cardiovascular diseases, type 2 diabetes, and other health complications. Among the options provided, **\"Obesity\"** is the correct major cause of metabolic syndromes.\r\n\r\nObesity, defined as excess body fat accumulation, particularly around the abdomen, has profound effects on various metabolic processes. It leads to insulin resistance, where cells become less responsive to the action of insulin, an essential hormone involved in glucose regulation. Insulin resistance can result in elevated blood glucose levels, contributing to the development of type 2 diabetes.\r\n\r\nMoreover, obesity is associated with dyslipidemia, characterized by high levels of triglycerides and low levels of high-density lipoprotein (HDL) cholesterol. This abnormal lipid profile, combined with hypertension and increased inflammation, further exacerbates the risk of cardiovascular diseases.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 486.","responses":[{"text":"Obesity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoglycemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased appetite","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased sleep","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypotension","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16053,"text":"When can glucagon and insulin be detected in the fetal plasma?","explanation":"In the context of glucagon and insulin detection in fetal plasma, the **correct time is between 10 to 15 weeks** of gestation. At this stage, the pancreatic islets, known as the **Islets of Langerhans**, have undergone significant development, and the beta cells start producing insulin, while the alpha cells produce glucagon.\r\n\r\nPrior to this period, during the **7-8 weeks** of gestation, the pancreas has already formed, but the islets and hormone production are not yet fully established. On the other hand, by the **11-13 weeks** and **15-20 weeks** marks, insulin and glucagon are already present in the fetal circulation, reflecting the maturation of the pancreatic endocrine function.","reference":"The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 219.","responses":[{"text":"11-13 weeks","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10-15 weeks","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"7-8 weeks","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"15-20 weeks","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"12-15 weeks","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16054,"text":"Which step of thyroid hormone synthesis will be affected by thiocyanate ions?","explanation":"The synthesis of thyroid hormones involves several crucial steps, and thiocyanate ions can impact one specific step, which is the **\"Entry of iodine into the thyroid cells.\"** Thyroid hormones, namely thyroxine (T4) and triiodothyronine (T3), are synthesized within the thyroid gland and are essential for regulating various metabolic processes in the body.\r\n\r\nThiocyanate ions (SCN-) competitively inhibit the **iodide (I-) symporter** present on the basolateral membrane of thyroid follicular cells. This symporter is responsible for transporting iodide ions from the bloodstream into the thyroid cells, a crucial early step in thyroid hormone synthesis. \r\n\r\nBy interfering with iodine entry, thiocyanate ions decrease the available substrate for the subsequent steps of thyroid hormone synthesis, thereby reducing the production of T3 and T4. Consequently, this leads to a condition known as **\"iodine deficiency goiter,\"** characterized by an enlarged thyroid gland due to its attempt to compensate for the inadequate production of thyroid hormones.\r\n\r\nTo summarize, **thiocyanate ions** affect the thyroid hormone synthesis process by **inhibiting the entry of iodine into the thyroid cells**, resulting in reduced hormone production and the development of goiter in cases of prolonged deficiency.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 950.","responses":[{"text":"Entry of iodine into the thyroid cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Coupling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Organification of thyroglobulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxidation of iodine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iodination of tyrosine","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

